    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER III.&mdash;MR. PEEBLES RECEIVES A MESSAGE.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">H</span>is lordship
      welcomed the appearance of the two young people as a relief from the
      further discussion of a painful topic.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;So, young madam,&rsquo; he said to Dulcie, pinching her ear, &lsquo;you&rsquo;ve come back!
      And where have you been all the afternoon?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;On the sands,&rsquo; said Dulcie. &lsquo;You&rsquo;re not angry with me, are you?&rsquo; she
      asked, kissing him in a coaxing fashion, for the tone in which he had
      spoken was a little sharp. &lsquo;I was so sorry to hear that you had been
      upset.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It wouldn&rsquo;t have happened if you had been at the table,&rsquo; said Kilpatrick.
      &lsquo;I suppose I have to thank <i>you</i>, sir,&rsquo; he continued to Desmond, &lsquo;for
      her absence? You&rsquo;re pretty spectacles, the pair of you,&rsquo; he went on,
      looking at the disordered dresses, flushed faces and untidy hair of the
      young couple. &lsquo;You&rsquo;ve been up to some mischief, I suppose?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Not this time,&rsquo; said Desmond, smiling. &lsquo;Hold your tongue, boy!&rsquo; snapped
      his lordship, with sudden and inexplicable ill-temper. &lsquo;Don&rsquo;t bandy words
      with me&mdash;hold your tongue!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, sir,&rsquo; said Desmond.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Can&rsquo;t you find something better to do than to go wandering about the
      place, mixing with all the loafers and blackguards in the county? Can&rsquo;t
      you speak? You can chatter fast enough when you&rsquo;re not asked to.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You told me to hold my tongue, sir,&rsquo; said Desmond, falling back on Irish
      prevarication and broadening his brogue.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I shall have to take some order with you, sir,&rsquo; said Kilpatrick. &lsquo;Come to
      my study to-morrow after breakfast. It&rsquo;s time you were doing something&mdash;time
      you began to think of&mdash;of your future. There, there,&rsquo; he continued,
      patting Desmond&rsquo;s shoulder, &lsquo;I&rsquo;m not angry with you, my boy. I&rsquo;ve been
      upset, and in my state of health the least thing excites me&mdash;ask
      Peebles.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ay,&rsquo; said the Scot, &lsquo;that&rsquo;s true&mdash;you&rsquo;ve a troublesome temper.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Never mind,&rsquo; said Dulcie; &lsquo;we&rsquo;ll coddle you up and comfort you. I&rsquo;ll play
      a game of backgammon with you, and if that doesn&rsquo;t cure you, I&rsquo;ll send
      over to Galway for mamma.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;For your mother!&rsquo; cried Kilpatrick. &lsquo;My sister Matilda!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;She&rsquo;s a capital nurse,&rsquo; said Dulcie. &lsquo;She&rsquo;ll set you right in a jiffy&mdash;as
      Desmond would say.&rsquo; The bit of slang passed unnoticed by his lordship in
      his terror at the suggestion it conveyed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Good heavens, child! Matilda will be praying over me day and night. I&rsquo;m
      not quite so bad as that&mdash;I won&rsquo;t be prayed over; but for this little
      cardiac weakness, I&rsquo;m in excellent condition. Ask Peebles. There, there,
      go and get your dinner, and take Desmond with you.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I shall come back afterwards,&rsquo; said Dulcie.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, yes!&rsquo; said her uncle. &lsquo;Come back by-and-by and give me my game of
      backgammon.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I met Mr. Blake on the road, sir,&rsquo; said Desmond. &lsquo;He asked me to deliver
      a message to your lordship.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well,&rsquo; snapped Kilpatrick, &lsquo;what has the drunken brute to say to me?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Just to apologize for what he did and said this afternoon.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;His repentance is mighty sudden,&rsquo; said Kilpatrick.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;He didn&rsquo;t repent at all till Desmond talked to him,&rsquo; said Dulcie, glad to
      get in a word in favour of her sweetheart.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;So you&rsquo;ve been giving Blake a lesson in manners, eh?&rsquo; said the old man.
      &lsquo;And what did you say to him, and how did he take it?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Desmond recounted the interview.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;He took it like mother&rsquo;s milk, sir. Sure he knew he was in the wrong.
      He&rsquo;s not a bad fellow, if you know how to humour him.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Peebles coughed behind his hand a dubious note, and Kilpatrick, catching
      the old man&rsquo;s eye, said with something of his former testiness:
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well, well, that will do&mdash;go and eat your dinner. Peebles, wait on
      Lady Dulcie.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The two young people and the old servitor left the room together, and
      Kilpatrick, sinking back into the seat he had quitted, sat for some time
      plunged in silent thought. Conseltine, leaning against the high,
      old-fashioned mantelpiece, took advantage of the shadow with which the
      room was filled, and of his brother&rsquo;s abstraction, to watch him narrowly.
      The old lord sighed once or twice, and gave one or two movements of
      impatience, and once the sound of a broken murmur reached Conseltine&rsquo;s
      ear, in which he distinguished only the word &lsquo;Moya.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Dick,&rsquo; said Kilpatrick, suddenly turning towards him, &lsquo;I must provide at
      once for Desmond&mdash;I simply must do it&mdash;I should be a cad if I
      didn&rsquo;t.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The intently watchful look which Conseltine&rsquo;s face had worn was replaced
      by his general expression of suavity as he came forward into the ray of
      light which was yet coming through the great oriel window.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;My dear Henry,&rsquo; he said smoothly, &lsquo;you are perfectly right. &rsquo;Tis
      the dictate of nature and justice&mdash;it does you credit.&rsquo; Kilpatrick,
      who was anything but a fool, looked at his brother with a curious, quick,
      questioning glance. Conseltine replied to it as if to a speech.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I know, my dear Henry, I know! You&rsquo;ve been thinking me grasping, and
      avaricious, and heartless, all this time, now, haven&rsquo;t you? And why? Just
      because I&rsquo;ve felt it my duty, as your brother and Richard&rsquo;s father, to
      safeguard the interests of the family. The title goes to Richard, anyhow;
      and &rsquo;tis but common-sense, as you said just now yourself, that the
      bulk of the property should go with it. &rsquo;Tis mighty little I can
      leave him, and a lord without soil to his foot or a guinea in his pocket
      would be a queer spectacle, wouldn&rsquo;t he? &rsquo;Tis not Lord Kilpatrick,
      anyhow, that shall be seen in that predicament; but you can provide for
      Desmond, too. You can give him all he has a right to expect, and still
      leave enough for Richard.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The argument was unanswerable, the manner and voice with which it was put
      were suave, persuasive, honest; but Kilpatrick&rsquo;s only answer was to shoot
      another quick, questioning glance at his brother&rsquo;s face, and to tap the
      carpet with his foot.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What would you call a proper provision?&rsquo; he asked, after an interval of
      silence.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Give the boy a profession, and&mdash;well, some hundreds a year. He&rsquo;s
      bright and clever, and with that income, and a calling in his fingers, if
      he can&rsquo;t make his way in the world, &rsquo;tis a pity.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;A profession!&rsquo; said Kilpatrick musingly. &lsquo;I don&rsquo;t know what the boy&rsquo;s fit
      for, unless it&rsquo;s for a soldier or a sailor.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Bad pay and poor prospects,&rsquo; said Conseltine. &lsquo;Why not the Church?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      His lordship went off into a sudden cackle of laughter.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;The Church! Fancy Desmond a priest! Faith, &rsquo;twould be a pretty
      parish that he had charge of!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;The bar?&rsquo; suggested his brother.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;No; Desmond hates lawyers almost as much as Blake himself&mdash;it&rsquo;s in
      the blood, I suppose&mdash;I&rsquo;m none too fond of them myself. I&rsquo;ll think it
      over, Dick, I&rsquo;ll think it over; don&rsquo;t bother me about it any more at
      present. Nothing shall be done without your knowledge and&mdash;without
      your knowledge, at all events.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You are tired?&rsquo; asked Conseltine.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, tired to death.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well, I&rsquo;ll leave you to yourself. Goodnight; sleep well, and you&rsquo;ll be as
      sound as a trout in the morning. I&rsquo;ll send up Peebles to help you to
      undress.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      He went; and Kilpatrick, rising from his seat, began to pace the room from
      end to end among the gathering shadows.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What the devil makes Dick Conseltine so tender all of a sudden?&rsquo; he asked
      himself. &lsquo;Dictate of nature and justice, indeed! He hates the boy like
      poison, that I&rsquo;m sure of. I can see it in his eye, sly and smooth as he
      is, every time he looks at him; and so does that bull-headed young fool,
      his son. It&rsquo;s natural, I suppose. Faith, then, one sees the hatred that
      money breeds&mdash;brother hating brother, father hating son, son father;
      the meanness, lying, ingratitude, intriguing; I&rsquo;d rather be the poorest
      peasant on my estate. I&rsquo;d rather be Desmond, poor boy; he knows his
      friends, at least. Nobody cajoles and flatters him.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      He fell silent again, and paced the room with a slower step.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Poor Moya! Gad! how it all comes back to me! If she had been only a
      little more of a lady, just a shade more possible as my wife! She was a
      lady in heart and feeling; the truest I ever met, I think. I threw away a
      jewel when I cast her off&mdash;nineteen years ago.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Nineteen years ago this month, and it is all as clear and vivid as if it
      had happened yesterday. Poor girl! I can see her face now as it was when I
      broke the secret to her. It will haunt me till I die, and after, if all
      tales are true. I was a scoundrel! It was a vile business. There are
      moments when I think Peebles is right: that it is my plain duty to let
      family considerations slide, own the boy, and leave him all. It wrings my
      heart to see him, handsome, manly, courageous, loved by everybody&mdash;my
      son! my own son!&mdash;and then look at that long-shanked cub of Dick&rsquo;s,
      and think that he, Desmond, is worth a million of him, worth a planetful
      of the stupid, ugly cur. How like his mother he is! Sometimes he frightens
      me; it is as if the dead came out of the grave to accuse me.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      He paused in his walk, and looked round the darkened chamber as if he
      feared an actual hidden presence there; then he walked to his desk, struck
      a match, and applied it to the wick of a small shaded reading-lamp; then,
      stealthily, and with more than one glance over his shoulder, he unlocked
      the desk, touched a spring, and drew from a secret drawer a scrap of paper
      and a miniature portrait. It was to the paper he gave his first attention.
      The writing, originally bold and heavy, had faded to a faint rusty red,
      the paper was stained and spotted. &lsquo;Take your child,&rsquo; he read falteringly;
      &lsquo;and as you use him may God use you.&rsquo; He sat staring at the flame of the
      lamp, blurred by the mist of gathering tears.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;As you use him, may God use you,&rsquo; he repeated half aloud. &lsquo;I&rsquo;ll do my
      duty by the boy&mdash;I <i>must!</i> Before God, if Moya were alive!&mdash;No,
      even that wouldn&rsquo;t mend matters&mdash;it wouldn&rsquo;t even mend her broken
      heart. It was not that she wasn&rsquo;t my lady&mdash;not that her vanity was
      wounded&mdash;it was the treachery! She loved me&mdash;she thought me an
      honest man. It was her pride in me that was broken. God forgive me! I
      acted like a villain!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      He took up the portrait and bent his eyes upon it with a long, regretful
      gaze. It was the work of a true artist, who had caught and reproduced with
      actual fidelity the features and expression of the proud and tender girl
      Kilpatrick had betrayed. The bright, gay face, instinct with youth and
      happiness, beamed from the picture; the sensitive lips seemed almost to
      tremble as the world-worn old man gazed at them. The dress was that of the
      better class of an Irish peasant of twenty years ago; but the hand which
      held the shawl about the throat wore jewelled rings.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;She sent back the rings&mdash;every scrap and every rag I&rsquo;d ever given
      her,&rsquo; said Kilpatrick. They lay in the secret drawer, and rattled as his
      blanched fingers drew them forth. &lsquo;She wouldn&rsquo;t wear the dress I&rsquo;d given
      her when she had this taken. &ldquo;Let me be as I was when you first knew me,
      when the great lord wasn&rsquo;t ashamed to tell the poor girl he loved her.&rdquo;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      With a sudden passionate gesture of love and remorse, he carried the
      picture to his lips.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;My lord!&rsquo; said a voice so startlingly close that it seemed to be at his
      very ear. Kilpatrick turned with a start and beheld a dim form standing in
      the shadow of the door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Confound you!&rsquo; he said. &lsquo;Who is it?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Just Peebles,&rsquo; said that worthy with his usual slow Scotch drawl.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Confound you,&rsquo; said his lordship again, &lsquo;why didn&rsquo;t you knock?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I knocked twice,&rsquo; said Peebles, &lsquo;and got nae answer. Mr. Conseltine told
      me ye needed me.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Kilpatrick dropped the letter and the miniature back into the desk and
      closed and locked it before speaking again.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Is Feagus still below?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ay,&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;He&rsquo;s drinking with Mr. Conseltine and Mr. Richard.
      He&rsquo;s just as drunk as a lord&mdash;begging your lordship&rsquo;s pardon. It&rsquo;s an
      old proverb, and like the most o&rsquo; proverbs, it has its exceptions.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Drunk, eh?&rsquo; said his lordship musingly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Verra drunk!&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;It&rsquo;s seldom he gets such liquor as comes out
      o&rsquo; your cellar, my lord.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I suppose so,&rsquo; said Kilpatrick absently; &lsquo;I suppose so. Well, you can
      help me to undress, Peebles, and then you can tell Mr. Feagus&mdash;you
      can tell him&mdash;tell him I&rsquo;ll write him regarding the business I have
      in hand.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Peebles, his face hidden in the darkness which surrounded the little
      circle of light cast by the reading-lamp, smiled sourly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Verra weel, my lord,&rsquo; he said; and Kilpatrick, rising, accepted his arm
      as a support to his bedroom.
    </p>
    <p>
      Half an hour later Peebles descended to the dining-room, where he found
      Mr. Feagus with his head on the table and one arm curled lovingly round an
      empty bottle.
    </p>
    <p>
      It took some trouble to rouse him, and even when awakened he was for a
      time oblivious of his surroundings. At last, dimly defining the figure of
      Peebles, he took him for Blake, and rising with a sort of paralytic
      alertness, bade the old man stand upon his defence. Peebles, from a safe
      distance, proclaimed his identity; thereupon the lawyer, relinquishing his
      pugnacious ardour, wept copiously, and would have embraced him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Gang hame&mdash;gang hame, now!&rsquo; said Peebles, repulsing him; thereupon
      Mr. Feagus&rsquo;s tears ran faster. &lsquo;My lord will send for ye if he should hae
      need o&rsquo; ye.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You&rsquo;ll come and have a drink with me, just for the sake of old times, Mr.
      Peebles?&rsquo; said Feagus.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ye&rsquo;ve had drink enough,&rsquo; said Peebles; &lsquo;gang hame!&rsquo; and bundled him
      through the French window opening on the lawn. Finding himself in the open
      air, Feagus made straight by instinct for the high road. Peebles stood at
      the window watching him tacking and reeling along the path until he had
      passed out of sight, and was about to return and close the window, when he
      heard a voice hailing him&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Misther Paybles! Misther Paybles!&rsquo; Peering into the darkness, he made out
      a dim form approaching him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Who is it?&rsquo; he asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;&rsquo;Tis me, sure&mdash;Larry.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Peebles recognised the lad, a henchman of Desmond&rsquo;s, a village loafer,
      generally to be found in the company either of the Squireen or of Lady
      Dulcie&rsquo;s maid, Rosie.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Weel, Larry! What hae ye there?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;&rsquo;Tis a letther!&rsquo; panted Larry.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;For my lord?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;No, &rsquo;tis for yourself.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And where did ye get it?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I met a poor woman at the foot o&rsquo; the hill, and she asked me if I knew
      one Misther Paybles. &ldquo;Sure I do,&rdquo; says I. &ldquo;Then,&rdquo; ses she, &ldquo;will ye earn
      the blessin&rsquo; on a poor craythur by givin&rsquo; this into his own hand?&rdquo; &ldquo;I
      will,&rdquo; ses I&mdash;and here I am.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Peebles accepted the scrap of paper Larry held out to him, and walking to
      the chimneypiece, read it by the light of the lamp: &lsquo;One who comes from
      Kenmare, and who knew Moya Macartney&rsquo;&mdash;he started, but, remembering
      Larry&rsquo;s presence, controlled himself and read on&mdash;&lsquo;would like to
      speak with him who was the best of friends to that poor colleen before she
      died. Will you meet the writer at ten tomorrow night in the churchyard by
      the lake-side and hear her message, for poor Moya&rsquo;s sake?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Peebles stood silent for a moment, the paper shaking in his fingers.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Who gave ye this, did ye say?&rsquo; he asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;A stranger,&rsquo; said Larry. &lsquo;She said there was no answer.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Verra weel,&rsquo; said Peebles, in a tone as near commonplace as he could make
      it. &lsquo;I&rsquo;ll attend to it.&rsquo; Larry saluted and vanished.
    </p>
    <p>
      Left alone, Peebles mused:
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What&rsquo;s the meaning of this? What mystery&rsquo;s here? A droll kind o&rsquo; message,
      and a droll kind o&rsquo; place for an appointment, and a droll hour o&rsquo; the
      night for a respectable man to be gadding about a kirkyard. Weel, weel!
      Maybe it&rsquo;s one of Moya&rsquo;s kin anxious to hear news aboot the bairn. Be she
      friend or foe, angel or deil, I&rsquo;ll be there.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
