      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER V.&mdash;LADY DULCIE OFFERS CONSOLATION.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">O</span>n Desmond&rsquo;s
      departure, Dulcie left the room, and ran swiftly to her own chamber. Her
      hurried ring at the bell was answered by her maid, Rosie.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Mr. Desmond has left the Castle,&rsquo; said Lady Dulcie. &lsquo;He has had a
      misunderstanding with his lordship. Follow him, and tell him not to leave
      the village till he sees me. Quick!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Sure, there&rsquo;s no hurry,&rsquo; said Rosie coolly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;But there is!&rsquo; cried Dulcie. &lsquo;The poor boy has quarrelled with Lord
      Kilpatrick, and vows that he will never come back.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;He&rsquo;ll not lave the place without sayin&rsquo; farewell to the boys at Widdy
      Daly&rsquo;s,&rsquo; said Rosie. &lsquo;There&rsquo;s a grand dance there to-night, and the whole
      counthryside will be there. I&rsquo;ll just go to the shebeen, and tell the
      widdy and the boys to kape on the watch for &lsquo;m, and lave word that I have
      a message for him from your ladyship.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Rosie&rsquo;s instinct had not deceived her, for that night Desmond was found
      sitting in the kitchen of the rude hostelry kept by the Widow Daly,
      listening to the strains of Patsey Doolan&rsquo;s fiddle, and sombrely watching
      the dance of boys and colleens, in which, for the first time during their
      long experience of him, he had declined to take part. Rosie delivered her
      message. Desmond heard it with a half-averted face, which did not hide
      from the girl&rsquo;s keen eyes a flush of pleasure on his cheek. He pressed her
      hand gratefully, but shook his head with a sad smile.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;&rsquo;Tis like her, Rosie&mdash;&rsquo;tis like her. But that&rsquo;s all
      over now. What can she have to say to a poor devil like me? She&rsquo;s up there
      with the reigning government of angels, and I&rsquo;m down here with the
      opposition. Well, never mind! The world&rsquo;s wide, and there&rsquo;s room in it
      somewhere for us all. Don&rsquo;t stand staring at me there, Rosie, as if I was
      a show in a fair. There&rsquo;s Larry dying to shake the rheumatism out of his
      legs. Play up, Patsey, you rogue, and put the music into their heels!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ye&rsquo;ll dance yourself, Mr. Desmond?&rsquo; said Rosie. &lsquo;I&rsquo;d be proud to stand
      out on the floor wid ye.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And, sure,&rsquo; said Larry, &lsquo;I wouldn&rsquo;t be jealous if ye did!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;No, no,&rsquo; said Desmond. &lsquo;Go and enjoy yourselves, and leave me to myself.
      Play up, play up!&rsquo; he shouted wildly, &lsquo;and the devil take the hindmost!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Rosie and Larry left him with pitying glances. The dance proceeded, the
      Squireen sitting apart and looking on with haggard eyes at the mirth he
      had so often shared.
    </p>
    <p>
      A sudden cessation of the music and the measured beat of feet upon the
      earthen floor made him look round. Lady Dulcie stood just within the door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Lady Dulcie!&rsquo; Desmond cried in astonishment, and rose and went towards
      her. &lsquo;What has brought you here?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;ve come to speak to you,&rsquo; she said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Desmond, I <i>must</i> speak to you.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;But,&rsquo; replied the boy, &lsquo;this is no place for you.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It&rsquo;s the place where <i>you</i> are,&rsquo; said the girl, with a tender look
      shining in her eyes, &lsquo;and that&rsquo;s enough for me.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Larry, standing arrested with his arm about Rosie&rsquo;s waist, caught the
      words.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;D&rsquo;ye hear that?&rsquo; he said to his partner. &lsquo;Clare out, boys,&rsquo; cried the
      widow. &lsquo;There&rsquo;s the rale stuff in the next room and in a moment, as if by
      magic, the whole company melted away,&mdash;only Larry and Rosie lingering
      at the door.
    </p>
    <p>
      Widow Daly wiped the seat of a stool for her guest, and set it for her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Sit ye down, my lady. Ye&rsquo;re kindly welcome.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Dulcie sat, looking up in Desmond&rsquo;s face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;She&rsquo;s the light of his eyes,&rsquo; whispered Rosie to her sweetheart. &lsquo;See how
      she looks at him.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ah!&rsquo; said Larry, &lsquo;when will ye be afther lookin&rsquo; at <i>me</i> like that?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;When your desarts are ayqual to your impudence!
    </p>
    <p>
      She curtsied, and drew Larry from the room after the others. The Widow
      Daly followed, dropping an ecstatic curtsey before she disappeared.
    </p>
    <p>
      There was a long pause. Desmond sat looking sadly at the fire.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Desmond!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, Lady Dulcie.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Dulcie to you, now and always,&rsquo; she said, taking his hand.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Don&rsquo;t, don&rsquo;t!&rsquo; said the lad. &lsquo;I can&rsquo;t bear it. I&rsquo;d rather you let me
      drift away from you like a leaf on the running water. I can bear all the
      rest, but not your pity.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It&rsquo;s not pity that brings me here,&rsquo; said the warm-hearted girl, with all
      her heart in her face. &lsquo;It&rsquo;s something more. I&rsquo;ve come to ask your
      forgiveness.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;My forgiveness!&rsquo; cried Desmond. &lsquo;For what?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;For all my foolish ways&mdash;my thoughtless words. I ought to have known
      better. But we were both so young. Well, I was a child this morning, but
      seeing your trouble, I feel to-night like an old, old woman.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ah! You&rsquo;re still what you always were, Dulcie, sweet and beautiful. &rsquo;Twas
      on a sunny summer&rsquo;s day God made ye, and &rsquo;Twas the brightest bit of
      work He ever did!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You&rsquo;re not going away, Desmond?&rsquo; she besought him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I must,&rsquo; he answered.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I came to ask you for your father&rsquo;s sake, for mine, to stay a little
      while. You will, Desmond? For my sake!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;They&rsquo;re words to conjure with, Dulcie,&rsquo; said Desmond. &lsquo;But sure I can&rsquo;t.
      D&rsquo;ye know what they&rsquo;ll all be calling me? D&rsquo;ye know what name they&rsquo;ll soon
      be giving me? How can I stay and look you in the face?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Oh, Desmond,&rsquo; she pleaded, &lsquo;your father&mdash;&mdash;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Don&rsquo;t spake of him!&rsquo; cried Desmond.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;He loves you, Desmond. He&rsquo;d give his right hand to put things right. If
      you will remain he will acknowledge you as his son&mdash;make you his
      heir.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Desmond shook his head.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;He can&rsquo;t give me the one thing I want,&rsquo; said Desmond proudly and sadly.
      &lsquo;He can&rsquo;t take the blot off my name, the stain off my mother&rsquo;s. He can&rsquo;t
      turn back the years and bring her from the grave.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;He can make amends,&rsquo; said Dulcie. &lsquo;He will.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It&rsquo;s too late for that, too,&rsquo; answered Desmond. &lsquo;Ah, spare me, Dulcie!
      Don&rsquo;t speak of it! Don&rsquo;t remind me of my disgrace!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Your disgrace?&rsquo; repeated Dulcie. &lsquo;Where is the disgrace to you? Where
      there is no sin there can be no shame; and you are innocent. Desmond,
      there are others who care for you. There&rsquo;s one,&rsquo; she added softly, &lsquo;who
      would give all the world to see you happy. Don&rsquo;t make her miserable by
      going away.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You mean that?&rsquo; cried the boy. &lsquo;No? Oh, Dulcie, don&rsquo;t be too good to me!
      Don&rsquo;t let me think you care for me!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Why not, when I do care for you?&rsquo; returned the girl. &lsquo;And I do, I do!&rsquo;
      She took his hand and rose from her seat. &lsquo;I think you&rsquo;re very
      ungrateful.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ungrateful! To <i>you!</i>&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes. You think me a child still, a doll, with no heart, or head, or will
      of my own. Ah! you don&rsquo;t know me. If you were to say, now, &ldquo;Dulcie, I want
      you,&rdquo; I&rsquo;d follow you to the end of the world.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Dulcie!&rsquo; He stretched his arms towards her, but fell back and let them
      drop at his sides again. &lsquo;I daren&rsquo;t! I mustn&rsquo;t! There&rsquo;s a great black
      river running between you and me.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Dulcie laughed with the old dashing spirit, so alien to his own.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Then show your pluck. Strip off your coat, plunge in, and swim across the
      river! I&rsquo;ll help you up the bank when you reach the other side.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Oh, Dulcie! my darling!&rsquo; Desmond caught her in his arms with a sudden
      gust of passion, and strained her to his breast.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Dulce, dulce domum!&rsquo; she said with another laugh, though her own eyes
      were brimming. &lsquo;You may <i>kiss</i> me if you like,&rsquo; she added with
      ineffable drollness. Choking with tears, he pressed his lips to her face.
      &lsquo;That&rsquo;s a dreadfully damp kiss. Sure, you&rsquo;ve swallowed the river. No, you
      shan&rsquo;t go. I&rsquo;ve got you, and I mean to keep you.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You&mdash;you love me, Dulcie?&rsquo; said Desmond, breathless with wonder and
      delight.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;A wee little bit,&rsquo; said Dulcie; &lsquo;just the least little bit in the world.
      Now, just sit down like a good sensible boy and listen to me. No more
      nonsense, if you please, about &ldquo;shame&rdquo; and &ldquo;disgrace.&rdquo; Our parents don&rsquo;t
      consult us as to the how and the where of our being born, and I don&rsquo;t see
      why we should trouble our heads about <i>them!</i> A boy&rsquo;s a boy, and a
      girl&rsquo;s a girl, and this boy and girl quite understand each other. Don&rsquo;t
      we?&rsquo; she asked, nestling up to him. &lsquo;I never knew you to be so backward
      before, Desmond! That river has washed all the old impudence out of you.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Her raillery could not altogether conquer Desmond&rsquo;s gloom.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It can&rsquo;t be, Dulcie. You&rsquo;re only opening the door to a fool&rsquo;s paradise
      for me. I&rsquo;ve lived in one long enough. &rsquo;Tis time I came out and
      looked at the world as it is. It can never be. It&rsquo;s madness to think of
      it. Even if it were different, even if the trouble had never fallen on me,
      I could never have hoped to win you. You&rsquo;re a lady. I&rsquo;m only the
      Squireen.&rsquo; &lsquo;You&rsquo;ve grown mighty humble all of a sudden,&rsquo; said Dulcie. &lsquo;You
      weren&rsquo;t like this only this afternoon. After I&rsquo;d waded with you across the
      pool, you had the impudence to kiss my shoes.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Sure I did,&rsquo; replied Desmond. &lsquo;And I&rsquo;m ready now to kiss your feet.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;That&rsquo;s better,&rsquo; said Dulcie, nestling nearer yet. &lsquo;That&rsquo;s more like the
      old Desmond. But a boy of taste would look a little higher. The mouth&rsquo;s
      prettier, and more &ldquo;convanient,&rdquo; as you&rsquo;d call it. Ah!&rsquo; she continued,
      with a sudden gush of tenderness, &lsquo;don&rsquo;t think me too bold! don&rsquo;t think me
      an outrageous little flirt! It wasn&rsquo;t till I felt your trouble that I knew
      my own heart, and learned that I loved you so much.&rsquo; She broke into a
      sudden sob. &lsquo;Tell me you&rsquo;re not miserable any more!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Miserable!&rsquo; cried Desmond, almost sobbing too; &lsquo;I&rsquo;m the most miserable
      and the happiest man in Ireland. But, oh, Dulcie, darling, I&rsquo;ve sworn&mdash;&mdash;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;But you mustn&rsquo;t!&rsquo; said Dulcie, laying her fingers on his lips. &lsquo;My
      sweetheart mustn&rsquo;t swear.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I mean, Dulcie, that while this shadow is over me I can never hold my
      head up again. I must leave this place. I&rsquo;ve neither land nor title,
      father nor mother&mdash;&mdash;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I don&rsquo;t want your land or your title,&rsquo; interrupted Dulcie, &lsquo;nor your
      father and mother. I want <i>you</i>, and I&rsquo;ve got you, and I shall keep
      you. Try to get away if you dare! You can&rsquo;t!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      A sound behind them made them both start, and, turning quickly, Desmond
      beheld Peebles standing in the doorway. He turned away to brush the tears
      from his eyes, but Dulcie hailed the intruder with delight.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Come in, Mr. Peebles,&rsquo; she cried, &lsquo;and talk to this stubborn boy. He
      won&rsquo;t listen to me a bit.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Is that so?&rsquo; said Peebles dryly, scratching at the scrap of gray whisker
      which decorated his cheek. &lsquo;I thought jest noo he seemed very attentive to
      your discourse! Desmond, laddie,&rsquo; he continued, &lsquo;my lord has sent me after
      you. Noo, noo, ye&rsquo;ll just hear me deliver my message. He&rsquo;s oot of his
      mind, almost, clean daft, and neither pancreatic emulsion nor leever pills
      will hae much power to help him through in this trouble, I&rsquo;m thinking.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Tell Lord Kilpatrick from me,&rsquo; said Desmond, when he could trust his
      voice, &lsquo;that I&rsquo;ve nothing more to say to him.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Hoot, lad!&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;Blood&rsquo;s thicker than water. Ye can&rsquo;t shake off
      the ties of relationship in that fashion, and cast awa&rsquo; your father like
      an old glove. For, after all, ye ken, he <i>is</i> your father.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;No!&rsquo; said Desmond. &lsquo;He&rsquo;s no father of mine.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Then he himself is sairly mista&rsquo;en,&rsquo; quoth the old servitor. &lsquo;He&rsquo;s been
      leevin&rsquo; for years under that impression!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;The man who broke my mother&rsquo;s heart is neither kith nor kin to me!
      Dulcie, good-bye! God bless you for all your goodness. You must try to
      forget me.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Oh, Desmond!&rsquo; cried the girl, &lsquo;you can&rsquo;t leave us; you can&rsquo;t, dear. Stay!
      Stay for my sake, I implore you!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;To be pointed at by everyone as the wretched thing I am. To know that my
      mother&rsquo;s name is a byword, and I myself am an outcast. You don&rsquo;t know what
      it is you ask me. &rsquo;Tis more than I can do.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;For my sake, Desmond!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I can&rsquo;t,&rsquo; cried the poor, proud boy; &lsquo;I can&rsquo;t, even for your sake.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And where are ye going?&rsquo; asked Peebles. &lsquo;Eh, Desmond, lad, what will ye
      do?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Do! Hide myself at any rate from those that have known me. The world&rsquo;s
      wide, old friend; don&rsquo;t fear for me!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      And he made a movement to the door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Stop!&rsquo; cried Peebles. &lsquo;Since ye <i>will</i> gang, listen to a word I hae
      to say to you. Never think shame o&rsquo; the mother that bore ye, Desmond. <i>I</i>
      kenned her, lad; I kenned her weel. She was a brave woman, as true and
      honest as she was loving, and &rsquo;twas for <i>your</i> sake that she
      took the weary road o&rsquo; death.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Desmond broke into sobs again, and the old man, seeing him thus softened,
      went on:
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;There&rsquo;s jest one thing ye&rsquo;ll promise me, lad. Before ye gang awa&rsquo;, see me
      once more, and maybe I can help ye yet.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;ll promise you that,&rsquo; said Desmond, &lsquo;if you&rsquo;ll give me a promise in
      return. You&rsquo;ll tell me all about my mother?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ay, lad, I&rsquo;ll tell ye all I ken. There&rsquo;s no word o&rsquo; shame for <i>her</i>
      in all the story, whatever shame there may be for others.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;All I think of now,&rsquo; continued Desmond, &lsquo;is the thought of the grief I
      brought her.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ne&rsquo;er believe it, lad,&rsquo; cried the old man; &lsquo;ne&rsquo;er believe it. Ye brought
      her comfort and hope.&rsquo; He wiped his eyes. &lsquo;Many&rsquo;s the time I&rsquo;ve grat o&rsquo;er
      your cradle, and noo, old fool that I am, I&rsquo;m greeting again. Bide a bit,
      lad; God may help us yet! There, there!&rsquo; he continued, as the impulsive
      young fellow threw his arms about him, &lsquo;ye&rsquo;ll not be for hugging old
      Peebles. Tak&rsquo; the little lass in your arms, and gie <i>her</i> one more
      kiss for luck!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Desmond!&rsquo; cried Dulcie, stretching her arms to him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;My conscience!&rsquo; said Peebles, as the lovers embraced, &lsquo;if I&rsquo;d your youth,
      and siccan a mouth to kiss, I wadna care if the Deil himsel&rsquo; was my
      progenitor!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Good-bye, my darling!&rsquo; sobbed Desmond. &lsquo;Good-bye, and God Almighty bless
      ye! I must go. Good-bye, good-bye!&rsquo; He tore himself from her arms, and ran
      out of the house. Dulcie sank back upon a bench, and her tears ran
      unrestrainedly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Tak&rsquo; heart, Lady Dulcie, tak&rsquo; heart,&rsquo; said the good old man, patting her
      shoulder with one hand, as he wiped his own eyes with the other. &lsquo;It&rsquo;s a
      sair trouble, but we&rsquo;ll maybe reconcile them yet.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Oh, Mr. Peebles!&rsquo; sobbed the girl. &lsquo;I love him!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Any fool could see that,&rsquo; said the old man, with a chuckle which was half
      a sob. &lsquo;I love him, too, the rascal! Ye must hasten home, Lady Dulcie. My
      lord needs watching, and &rsquo;tis weel ye should be with him, for the
      boy&rsquo;s sake.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Dulcie dried her tears, and called Rosie, who answered the summons at
      once.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You&rsquo;ll take care of him?&rsquo; she said to Peebles. &lsquo;You&rsquo;ll see that he comes
      to no harm?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Trust me for that,&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;There, there, my bonny doo, tak&rsquo;
      comfort. He&rsquo;ll be yours yet.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Oh, how good you are!&rsquo; cried Dulcie. She threw her arms about his neck,
      and kissed him on either cheek with right goodwill. &lsquo;That&rsquo;s for Desmond&rsquo;s
      sake. Mind, I trust in <i>you</i>.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Left alone, Peebles stood for some moments in a cataleptic condition, till
      he recovered his senses, and refreshed his brain with a liberal pinch of
      snuff from his waistcoat pocket.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Peebles, ye old villain!&rsquo; he said to himself, &lsquo;what&rsquo;s gone wi&rsquo; your
      morality, lettin&rsquo; the lassies kiss you at your age! Aweel! a kiss like
      that from a pure lass is better than a bad man&rsquo;s blessing. Never fear,
      Lady Dulcie, nae mischief shall befall Desmond Macartney if I can save
      him.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0006" id="link2HCH0006"> </a>
