    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER VI.&mdash;THE MEETING IN THE GRAVEYARD.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">T</span>hat same night a
      cold round moon was shining on the old graveyard where the people of
      Kilpatrick had for many generations buried their dead&mdash;a place of
      green and grassy graves, with here and there a simple cross of stone or
      wood. It was a lonely place, a lonely hour, and with the rising moon came
      a chilly night wind, stealing from grave to grave, and lifting the grass
      upon them as a cold hand might lift the hair of human heads.
    </p>
    <p>
      The silence of the spot was broken by the sound of a slow but firm
      footstep approaching along the quiet by-road that led to the village. A
      tall woman, with a shawl about her head, and clad in a material so dark as
      to pass for black in the moonlight, entered the graveyard, and stood
      looking towards the distant sea. She looked long and earnestly before she
      spoke.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It&rsquo;s the time I named,&rsquo; she murmured in a deep, inward-sounding voice.
      &lsquo;Will he come, I wonder? Maybe he&rsquo;ll think it&rsquo;s an idle message, and never
      guess who sent it, for he thinks me dead and gone long years ago. I must
      speak with him, and hear tidings of my boy. Oh, saints in heaven, that
      know the achings of a mother&rsquo;s heart, ye&rsquo;ve given me strength to bear my
      trouble all these years&mdash;give me strength now, and pity the wakeness
      that brought me here, maybe to get a glimpse of my darling son!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      She leaned against a ragged, wind-blown tree, with her forehead supported
      on her arm; then, slipping to the ground, bent her head in prayer&mdash;an
      appeal of which only an occasional word could have been heard by any
      chance listener, though the fervour of her supplication shook her whole
      body with a passionate tremor. She was so lost for the moment to all sense
      of her surroundings that a loud and cheerful whistle, coming along the
      path she had herself travelled but a few minutes previous, fell unheeded
      on her ear, and the gravedigger, returning for his pick and shovel, was
      close upon her before she recognised his presence.
    </p>
    <p>
      She rose with a start, and the suddenness of her apparition made the
      intruder&rsquo;s music stop with a ludicrous suddenness.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Musha!&rsquo; he cried. &lsquo;What&rsquo;s that at all? &rsquo;Tis a woman! Bedad, I took
      ye for a ghost!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;m flesh and blood, like yourself,&rsquo; she answered.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;But why were ye kneeling there?&rsquo; he asked, still fearfully.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I was only saying a prayer,&rsquo; she answered.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;A mighty lonesome place to say your prayers in,&rsquo; said the gravedigger,
      crossing himself. &lsquo;Unless,&rsquo; he added as an afterthought, and more gently,
      &lsquo;ye&rsquo;ve any kith or kin lying here.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;No,&rsquo; said the woman; &lsquo;I am a stranger.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well, good luck t&rsquo; ye, whoever y&rsquo; are,&rsquo; said the gravedigger. &lsquo;I&rsquo;ll just
      get the pick and the spade, and lave ye to your devotions.&rsquo; He jumped into
      an open grave at a little distance. &lsquo;I can finish this in the morning,&rsquo; he
      added to himself. &lsquo;Another two feet &rsquo;ll do it.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Who&rsquo;s to be buried there?&rsquo; she asked, as he clambered out with his tools
      in his hand.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;A poor colleen that kilt herself for love. Leastways, she drowned
      herself, but wint out of her mind first, to make sure of Christian burial.
      Are ye livin&rsquo; hereabouts, my woman?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes,&rsquo; she answered. &lsquo;I&rsquo;ve a lodging down at the old mill.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Musha!&rsquo; said the gravedigger, &lsquo;that&rsquo;s a lonesome place.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;The more fit, maybe,&rsquo; she answered, &lsquo;for a lonesome woman.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Will ye be going now?&rsquo; asked the man, looking at her with some anxiety.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Presently,&rsquo; she answered. &lsquo;Sure, I&rsquo;m doing no harm.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Sorra the bit,&rsquo; he said; &lsquo;but I&rsquo;m thinking that there&rsquo;s not many women&mdash;nor
      men ayther, for that matter&mdash;who&rsquo;d care to walk this graveyard at
      night, when the fairies walk it. Well, tastes differ, and so good luck t&rsquo;
      ye.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And good luck to <i>you!</i>&rsquo; the woman answered.
    </p>
    <p>
      The man shouldered his tools and went off, resuming his interrupted
      whistle. The woman looked anxiously down the road.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It&rsquo;s past the time I named,&rsquo; she said to herself, &lsquo;and no sign of him
      yet.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      She walked to the low wall which separated the graveyard from the road,
      and stood there, watching so keenly that the sound of a footstep
      approaching from the opposite side of the churchyard failed to wake her
      attention. The unseen wayfarer, who was no other than Mr. Feagus,
      returning homewards after a wettish evening with a client beyond the
      village, caught sight of her tall, gaunt figure clearly outlined against
      the pale flood of moonlight which deluged the sky.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Who&rsquo;s that, now?&rsquo; he asked himself, with a start,&mdash;&lsquo;a woman, or a
      taisch?&mdash;a Christian soul, or an ugly spirit? Wake my soul to glory!
      I&rsquo;m sorry I took this road, for it&rsquo;s lonesome for a lawyer with long
      arrears of conscience to make up; and, faith, here&rsquo;s another of &rsquo;em
      coming the way I came myself. No, &rsquo;tis a man this time, a living
      man, bless the saints! I&rsquo;ll step along with him for company. Am I drunk or
      dreamin&rsquo;? &rsquo;Tis that old omadhaun, Peebles the steward! &rsquo;Tis
      mighty queer! What can bring a quiet man like that down here at
      night-toime? If it&rsquo;s an assignation with that female? The old rascal! I&rsquo;ll
      keep out of his way, and watch what he&rsquo;s after.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      He slid cautiously over the wall, and established himself in the deepest
      shadow, just as Peebles&rsquo; lean figure emerged into clear moonlight.
    </p>
    <p>
      The old man paused at the wicket-gate.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I saw someone here&mdash;I&rsquo;d swear till it, and noo there&rsquo;s nae sign of
      any living thing. Lord save us! it&rsquo;s a gruesome place. Well, gruesome or
      no gruesome, I&rsquo;ll e&rsquo;en see it through. She&rsquo;s there!&rsquo; he exclaimed,
      catching sight of the woman&rsquo;s figure. &lsquo;Ahem! Was&rsquo;t you, lass, that sent
      the message to Mr. Peebles?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The woman turned eagerly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, sir!&rsquo; she cried. &lsquo;I sent for you!&rsquo; &lsquo;Good e&rsquo;en t&rsquo; ye, whoever ye
      are,&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;I&rsquo;m here at your service, though I ken little enough
      what it is ye want o&rsquo; me. &rsquo;Twas of Moya Macartney ye wanted to
      speak&mdash;the puir lassie that died lang syne?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Of Moya Macartney, sure enough,&rsquo; answered the woman. &lsquo;But she never died,
      sir. She&rsquo;s alive this day, and nearer than ye think!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Lord save us!&rsquo; exclaimed Peebles. &lsquo;You say she&rsquo;s living! Moya Macartney
      living?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The woman turned her face to the moonlight, and let her shawl, which had
      hidden it, fall back upon her shoulders. The old man stepped nearer,
      peering on her with a look of mingled expectation, incredulity, and
      superstitious horror. The face was white, thin, and wrinkled, but he
      recognised it in a moment; and as the great black eyes dwelt on Peebles&rsquo;
      face, the thin lips murmured a name which struck on his astonished ears
      like a veritable echo from the grave.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Moya!&rsquo; he cried. &lsquo;Moya Macartney! No! It can&rsquo;t be!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It is, sir,&rsquo; said Moya. &lsquo;I&rsquo;m Moya Macartney. Old and gray now, Mr.
      Peebles, but the same colleen ye knew once in Kenmare.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The hidden listener raised his head cautiously.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Saints preserve us!&rsquo; he muttered, and taking advantage of Peebles&rsquo; wonder
      and consternation, crept nearer to him and his companion.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Meeracle of meeracles!&rsquo; cried the old man. He extended a trembling hand,
      and took that which Moya held out in answer. It was as real as, and warmer
      and steadier than, his own. &lsquo;Ay! ye&rsquo;re flesh and blood; but&mdash;what
      does it mean?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Sure, it&rsquo;s a long story,&rsquo; said Moya; &lsquo;but I&rsquo;ll tell it ye in as few words
      as I can. When I left my child and went away broken-hearted, I little
      thought to live another day; but my courage failed me, and I feared to
      face my Maker before my time. I lived on, unknown and far away. But I
      heard news from time to time of my son. I knew that he was growing up
      happy, and ignorant, thank God, of his mother&rsquo;s shame.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Puir lass!&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;Puir lass! And it&rsquo;s been for his own sake that
      ye&rsquo;ve held aloof from him all these years&mdash;never shown your face or
      spoke a word!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Sure, why should I? &rsquo;Twas enough for me to think that maybe, when
      he thought that I was dead, my lord&rsquo;s heart might be turned to the poor
      friendless boy, and that he might crape into his father&rsquo;s heart and earn
      his love. I said to myself a thousand times, &ldquo;God bless him! I&rsquo;ll never
      disgrace him. He shall never learn that his mother&rsquo;s still living on this
      weary earth.&rdquo;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;But ye&rsquo;ve come at last, Moya,&rsquo; said Peebles, wiping his eyes; &lsquo;ye&rsquo;ve come
      at last to&mdash;&mdash;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Only to hear of his happiness&mdash;only, maybe, to get one glimpse of
      his face. Oh, sir, if I could do that same, I&rsquo;d die happy, for the
      heaviness of years is on me, and I&rsquo;ve not long to live. Speak to me! Tell
      me of him! Is he well and happy?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Weel?&rsquo; repeated Peebles. &lsquo;Ay, he&rsquo;s weel enough. Happy? Ay, he&rsquo;s as happy
      as most folk, for it&rsquo;s a wearyin&rsquo; world.&rsquo; He paused, looking pityingly at
      Moya, and then resumed in a hesitating manner: &lsquo;I&rsquo;ve news for ye that I
      fear will not be over welcome to ye. &rsquo;Twas only yesterday he
      learned the truth. He found oot that Lord Kilpatrick was his father, and
      with that, poor lad, he shook the dust from his feet and fled away from
      his father&rsquo;s house.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;My God!&rsquo; cried Moya. &lsquo;But who tould him? Not you, sure?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I?&rsquo; cried Peebles&mdash;&lsquo;I, that hae guarded the secret these eighteen
      years, and burdened my conscience with endless lees for the poor lad&rsquo;s
      sake and yours! No, no, Moya. He was taunted wi&rsquo; his birth by a wicked
      whelp&mdash;his cousin, Richard Conseltine&rsquo;s son, and a&rsquo; came oot.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And then?&rsquo; cried Moya.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;My lord begged him to stay, offered to make him his lawful heir, but he
      refused the siller and cursed his father in his mother&rsquo;s name. Ah, don&rsquo;t
      greet, woman, or I&rsquo;ll be greeting too. Your name&rsquo;s deepest in the lad&rsquo;s
      heart, and first upon his lips.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;God bless him!&rsquo; sobbed the heartbroken mother. &lsquo;But what shall I do? What
      shall I do?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Let me take ye to him,&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;Eh, lass, but the boy&rsquo;s heart will
      leap for joy to know ye&rsquo;re alive.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;No!&rsquo; said Moya, shrinking back. &lsquo;No, no! Let things be as they are. It&rsquo;s
      betther, far betther, that he should think me dead.
    </p>
    <p>
      Alive, I shall only shame him more. Just let me see him, let me look into
      his eyes and hear his voice&mdash;&rsquo;tis all I ask of the blessed
      saints, and I&rsquo;ll go back to where I came from and never trouble him
      again.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      At that moment, as if in answer to the impassioned prayer of that lonely
      heart, a voice rose at a hundred yards&rsquo; distance. Peebles started at the
      sound:
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      &lsquo;Tho&rsquo; I lave thee for ever, my darling, and go,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Thine image shall haunt me in sunshine and
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      snow;
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Like the light of a star shining over the foam,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Thy face shall go with me wherever I roam.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Lord save us!&rsquo; cried Peebles. &lsquo;&rsquo;Tis himself.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Who?&rsquo; cried Moya wildly. &lsquo;Desmond? My son?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ay! your son Desmond. Wheest, woman! He&rsquo;s coming this way.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      &lsquo;Though waves roll between us, sweet star of my
    </p>
    <p class="indent30">
      love,
    </p>
    <p class="indent15">
      Thy voice calls unto me&mdash;&mdash;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      <br />
    </p>
    <p>
      Desmond&rsquo;s voice rose again as he spoke, nearer and more distinct.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Mr. Peebles!&rsquo; he cried, pausing in his song to scrutinize his old
      friend&rsquo;s figure in the moonlight. &lsquo;It&rsquo;s late for you to be out here among
      the graves. Who&rsquo;s that with ye?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Peebles hesitated. Moya touched him lightly on the arm.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It&rsquo;s just a poor peasant body. She&rsquo;s strange to these parts, and was
      asking the way.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Moya had gathered her shawl about her face again, and a sob broke from
      her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Sure she&rsquo;s in trouble,&rsquo; Desmond added pityingly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, sir,&rsquo; said Moya, conquering herself, &lsquo;I&rsquo;m in bitter trouble. And by
      the same token there&rsquo;s trouble in <i>your</i> heart too.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;In mine?&rsquo; said Desmond, forcing a laugh, not very successfully.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ye favour one I used to know,&rsquo; said Moya. &lsquo;Will ye tell me your name,
      sir?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;My name?&rsquo; said Desmond hesitatingly. &lsquo;Well, why not? My name&rsquo;s Desmond
      Macartney.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Desmond Macartney!&rsquo; the woman repeated. &lsquo;I&rsquo;ll not forget it. Sure I&rsquo;d
      once a boy of me own, as swate to look upon as yourself. It&rsquo;s proud your
      mother should be of such a son.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;My mother is dead,&rsquo; said Desmond. &lsquo;She died long ago&mdash;when I was but
      a child. Good-night t&rsquo; ye, and God help ye through your trouble.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Where are you going, Desmond?&rsquo; asked Peebles.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;To the farm yonder; they&rsquo;ll put me up for the night.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Wait for me there to-morrow. I must see you.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;ll wait,&rsquo; said Desmond. He looked again at Moya, who was crying
      unrestrainedly. &lsquo;Poor soul!&rsquo; he said. &lsquo;She seems to have a heavy grief.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;She has,&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;She&rsquo;s lost all the folk she loves.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Like me,&rsquo; sighed Desmond. &lsquo;Well, well! &ldquo;Though I lave thee for ever,&rdquo;&rsquo; he
      began singing again as he turned away, till interrupted by the stranger&rsquo;s
      voice.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Sir&mdash;Mr. Desmond!&rsquo; cried the woman suddenly, &lsquo;they say that the
      blessing o&rsquo; one broken heart may help to heal the trouble of another. Will
      ye bend down in this holy place and take a poor creature&rsquo;s blessing?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Sure,&rsquo; said Desmond, &lsquo;it&rsquo;s only one blessing in the whole world that I
      seek, and that I can never have&mdash;the blessing of my own dead mother.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Maybe it might come through me! I&rsquo;m a mother, too!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Humour her, laddie,&rsquo; said Peebles gently. &lsquo;Humour her. Her sorrow&rsquo;s
      great.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Desmond took off his cap and knelt with bent head. It seemed long before
      the voice broke the solemn stillness, but when at last it was audible, it
      was strangely firm.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;May the Lord watch over ye, now and for ever! May the mouth of the mother
      that bore ye spake through me, and bring ye happiness, health, and peace.
      May your days be long in the land, till you&rsquo;re old and gray like me. But,
      oh, may ye never know my trouble or lose what I have lost. Amen! Amen!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And may God bless <i>you!</i>&rsquo; said Desmond, rising, deeply touched by
      the solemn words and the deep rich voice which had spoken them.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And now,&rsquo; said Moya, &lsquo;will ye let a poor crathure kiss your forehead, for
      the sake of her own son that she&rsquo;ll never see again?&rsquo; She took his head
      between her hands and pressed her lips to his brow in a long embrace. &lsquo;The
      Lord be with you, Desmond Macartney.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      With no other word, she turned and left the graveyard, Peebles following
      her after a hasty reminder to Desmond of their engagement for the morrow.
    </p>
    <p>
      It was not till some minutes later, when Desmond&rsquo;s voice rose again on the
      air at a considerable distance, and the figures of Moya and Peebles had
      disappeared, that Feagus rose to his feet.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Monomondiaoul!&rsquo; he said softly to himself. &lsquo;Moya Macartney alive! And
      what will me lord and Mr. Conseltine say to that, I wonder?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0007" id="link2HCH0007"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER VII.&mdash;BLAKE, OF BLAKE&rsquo;S HALL.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">L</span>ady Dulcie,
      wending her way back from the shebeen to the Castle under the escort of
      Rosie and the faithful Larry, dried her tears resolutely, and did her best&mdash;no
      hard task at sweet eighteen, with love as an ally&mdash;to look on the
      bright side of things. Desmond would never leave her for long, of that she
      felt assured. He might go out into the world to seek his fortune, and, of
      course, one so brave, generous, handsome, and altogether admirable, could
      hardly fail to find it; but his success or failure would never, she told
      herself, make any difference to her. The day was not far off when she
      would be her own mistress, and then no spite of accident or design should
      hold her from her lover&rsquo;s arms.
    </p>
    <p>
      As she and her companions came upon the confines of the Castle grounds two
      dusky figures approached them, and she made out by the faint light of the
      rising moon that they were Mr. Conseltine and his son Richard. They
      saluted her silently, to her great relief, and she passed by.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;She&rsquo;s been to meet that blackguard bastard, I suppose,&rsquo; muttered Richard
      between his teeth. &lsquo;Damn him!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;With all my heart!&rsquo; responded his senior. &lsquo;Damn him, by all means! Your
      blunder of the morning has turned out better than I had dared to hope; but
      it was a blunder all the same.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It might have been,&rsquo; returned Richard; &lsquo;but, so far, it has answered.
      We&rsquo;ve got the brute out of the house, and it won&rsquo;t be my fault if he gets
      in again.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;&rsquo;Twas too bold a stroke, lad,&rsquo; said Conseltine. &lsquo;You show your
      cards too openly&mdash;you play too boldly. If the proud-stomached young
      ass had only had a little common-sense, he might have consolidated his
      position with your uncle. Henry was in the mood to do anything, to commit
      any folly, after you insulted the boy.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I couldn&rsquo;t help it,&rsquo; returned Richard. &lsquo;I hate the cad to such an extent
      that I&rsquo;d have shouted his shame in his face if it had cost me every penny
      I have and every penny I expect from Kilpatrick.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You&rsquo;re a fool,&rsquo; said his father, smoothly as ever. It required a good
      deal to shake the elder Conseltine from his calm cynicism. &lsquo;And if you
      think the game&rsquo;s won just because you&rsquo;ve insulted the Squireen and got him
      out of the Castle for a single day, you&rsquo;re a bigger fool than I ever
      thought you&mdash;and that&rsquo;s not saying a little. The game&rsquo;s only begun.
      Henry&rsquo;s fond of the brat&mdash;absence will make him fonder still. It&rsquo;s
      quite on the cards that he may leave every stick and stone of his property
      to him and strand you with the barren title. Keep out of his way. He never
      liked you, and now he likes you less than ever. Leave him to me. Leave
      Dulcie alone, too. Don&rsquo;t be trying to excuse yourself, or trying to make
      love to her; you&rsquo;ll only make bad a deal worse. Who&rsquo;s that in front of us?&mdash;your
      eyes are younger than mine.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It&rsquo;s that drunken scoundrel Blake.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Blake!&rsquo; repeated Conseltine, and fell into a slower step. &lsquo;Well, &rsquo;tis
      lucky, on the whole. &rsquo;Tis as well he should know.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Know what?&rsquo; asked Richard.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Know all there is to be known about this business of the Squireen,&rsquo;
      answered the elder.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What affair is it of his?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;That you&rsquo;ll not learn from me,&rsquo; responded his father: &lsquo;not yet, at least.
      If it&rsquo;s ever necessary you should know, I&rsquo;ll tell you. Meanwhile, keep a
      still tongue and an open eye. It&rsquo;s to the shebeen he&rsquo;s going&mdash;we&rsquo;ll
      follow him.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      They were close behind Blake&rsquo;s heels by the time he had reached the door
      of the alehouse. He lurched round and faced them.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;The divil and his imp,&rsquo; he remarked, as a polite salutation, and stumbled
      across the threshold with no further greeting than a drunken laugh.
    </p>
    <p>
      Peebles was in the kitchen, finishing a drink of whisky, and chatting with
      the widow.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Hullo! my king o&rsquo; Scots,&rsquo; hiccuped Blake. &lsquo;You here? Drinkin&rsquo;, too! Ye&rsquo;ve
      taken to decent habits in your old age. Here! you&rsquo;ll have another drink
      with me.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Indeed but I&rsquo;ll no&rsquo;,&rsquo; replied the sententious old Scot.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You won&rsquo;t! You won&rsquo;t drink?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, with my friends,&rsquo; returned Peebles; &lsquo;but I see none o&rsquo; them <i>here</i>.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      He set his glass upon the table, nodded to the widow, and went out to keep
      his already recorded interview with Moya in the churchyard.
    </p>
    <p>
      Blake laughed with drunken good humour.
    </p>
    <p>
      &rsquo;Tis a brave boy, old Peebles! He doesn&rsquo;t trust me, but, after all,
      &rsquo;tis a question of taste, and no gentleman quarrels on such a
      ground. Bedad, I&rsquo;m dry.&rsquo; He searched his pockets, and found them empty.
      &lsquo;Here, you spalpeen,&rsquo; he continued, accosting Richard, &lsquo;pay for a drink
      for me. Sure, &rsquo;twill be a luxury for you, and one you don&rsquo;t often
      enjoy.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Bring some whisky, if you please, Mrs. Daly,&rsquo; said Conseltine smoothly,
      before Richard could muster his heavy wits to retort. &lsquo;Sit down, Blake,
      and listen to me. Are ye sober enough to talk business?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;m as sober as I need be,&rsquo; responded Blake; &lsquo;and more sober than I want
      to be, at this hour o&rsquo; the night.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;That&rsquo;s easily cured,&rsquo; said Conseltine dryly, handing him a charged
      tumbler; &lsquo;but don&rsquo;t go too fast&mdash;this is business.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Discoorse,&rsquo; said Blake, tossing off the spirit, &lsquo;and I&rsquo;ll listen.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The widow still lingered about the room, making pretence of trifling with
      some household task. Conseltine with a smooth voice bade her leave them to
      themselves, and she obeyed, after which he rose, and for greater security
      closed the door leading to the road.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ye&rsquo;re mighty mysterious,&rsquo; said Blake. &lsquo;What is it, at all?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Have you heard what happened at the Castle this morning?&rsquo; asked
      Conseltine, leaning across the rude table at which the two were seated,
      and speaking in a whisper.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;How the divil should I?&rsquo; asked Blake.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;ve not been out of bed an hour, and I&rsquo;d be there still, but the whisky
      gave out, and I kem here to wet my whistle.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;&rsquo;Tis better ye should hear it from me than from another,&rsquo; said
      Conseltine, in the same tone of extreme caution. &lsquo;My son here made a fool
      of himself this morning.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Did he, now?&rsquo; returned Blake, with a laugh. &lsquo;Sure his Creator did that
      for him twenty years ago.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;He had a row with the Squireen, young Desmond Macartney, and let out what
      he knew about his birth.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;&rsquo;Tis the first time I knew that he knew anything about it,&rsquo; said
      Blake. &lsquo;Was it you that trusted him with such a secret?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Never mind how he came to know,&rsquo; returned Conseltine. &lsquo;He learned the
      secret. Desmond provoked him, and he blurted it out before everybody&mdash;Lady
      Dulcie, my brother, Peebles and all.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And he&rsquo;s here to tell the tale?&rsquo; said Blake, with an air of drunken
      surprise. &lsquo;Bedad, I&rsquo;m a good man with my fists, but &rsquo;tis not I that
      would like to tell the Squireen that story.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Listen! Listen!&rsquo; said Conseltine, beating the tops of his fingers on the
      table a little impatiently.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;D&rsquo;ye mean to sit there, Dick Conseltine,&rsquo; said Blake, &lsquo;an&rsquo; tell me that
      that rip of a son o&rsquo; yours told the Squireen all that, and there was no
      fight?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Devil a bit of a fight,&rsquo; answered Conseltine. &lsquo;The boy was knocked clean
      out of time by the information. Well, when he came to, his lordship told
      him he&rsquo;d acknowledge him before the world.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;His lordship&rsquo;s a gentleman!&rsquo; cried Blake. &lsquo;By the Lord, he is! If only he
      could hold a dacent skinful o&rsquo; liquor, he&rsquo;d be the finest gentleman in
      Ireland, bar none. And what did the Squireen say?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;He cursed the father that begot him,&rsquo; returned Conseltine. &lsquo;He shook the
      dust of the house off his feet, and swore he&rsquo;d never cross the threshold
      again!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Then the boy&rsquo;s like his father&mdash;a gentleman!&rsquo; cried Blake, with a
      drunken cheer. &lsquo;Here&rsquo;s to him, with three times three and all the honours!
      And what did the old man say to that?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It has made him seriously ill,&rsquo; answered Conseltine. &lsquo;He has passed the
      day in bed, and has refused himself to everybody except Peebles. Now,
      Blake,&rsquo; he leaned further across the table, and fixed his keen eyes on the
      face of the drunken squire, &lsquo;the time has come for a definite
      understanding between us.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well?&rsquo; asked Blake. He made an obvious and partially successful attempt
      to sober himself. &lsquo;Give me that jug o&rsquo; water.&rsquo; It was passed to him, and
      he drained it&mdash;to the great apparent refreshment and steadying of his
      wits. &lsquo;A man has need of all his brains, Dick Conseltine, when ye speak in
      that tone of voice. Out with it&mdash;what hell-broth are ye brewing now?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;There&rsquo;s no new development yet,&rsquo; answered Conseltine, with a smile,
      &lsquo;though something may occur at any moment with Henry in his present
      condition. But I want to know definitely, yes or no, are you for us or
      against us?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;That just depends on how ye treat me,&rsquo; muttered Blake. &lsquo;I don&rsquo;t know
      whether it is that I&rsquo;m getting old, or whether the whisky is playing false
      with my nerves&mdash;which is what I&rsquo;d call my conscience, if I was one o&rsquo;
      the pious sort&mdash;or what it is, but I&mdash;I fluctuate! Sometimes&mdash;it&rsquo;s
      generally in the morning, when I wake&mdash;I feel penitent: I feel that
      I&rsquo;d like to go over to the enemy and clear my breast o&rsquo; the load I&rsquo;ve
      borne this eighteen years and more. What are ye doin&rsquo;?&rsquo; he asked angrily,
      as Conseltine trod heavily on his foot beneath the table. &lsquo;Oh, the cub!
      Sure I said nothin&rsquo; that he has the brains to understand. Yes, Mr. Richard
      Conseltine, that&rsquo;s how I feel at times, and it comes over me generally in
      the mornin&rsquo;, when the whisky&rsquo;s out and my pockets are empty. And, by
      thunder, if I did! if I did tell all I know&mdash;Holy Moses! what a
      racket it would make up at the Castle, and all Ireland over. Faith, I&rsquo;d
      live in history! &rsquo;Twould be what the play-actors call a fine
      situation! And let me tell ye, there&rsquo;s them as &rsquo;d make it worth me
      while to do it!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You drunken hog!&rsquo; murmured Conseltine under his breath; adding aloud,
      &lsquo;You won&rsquo;t do that, Blake!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Won&rsquo;t I?&rsquo; returned Blake. &lsquo;Faith, you&rsquo;re surer about it than I am!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;No,&rsquo; said Conseltine, &lsquo;you won&rsquo;t do it. I can make it better worth your
      while to keep silent.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Then why the divil don&rsquo;t ye?&rsquo; asked Blake. &lsquo;You&rsquo;re very fond o&rsquo; talking
      about your gratitude, and you hold out fine promises, but what do ye <i>do?</i>&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It seems to me,&rsquo; returned the other, &lsquo;that I&rsquo;ve done a good deal.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And it seems to me,&rsquo; exclaimed Blake, banging the table to emphasize the
      personal pronoun, &lsquo;that ye do damn&rsquo;d little. I tell ye, Dick Conseltine,
      it&rsquo;s not for nothing that I&rsquo;m going to suffer the torments of an aching
      conscience!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Your aching conscience,&rsquo; said Conseltine, with a scarcely perceptible
      sneer, &lsquo;has been fairly well salved so far. Is it money that you want?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Bedad it is, then!&rsquo; cried the other. &lsquo;I haven&rsquo;t the price of a glass in
      the wide world.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well,&rsquo; said his fellow conspirator, &lsquo;I&rsquo;m willing to do what I can, in
      reason.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;In reason!&rsquo; repeated Blake. &lsquo;Your notions of what&rsquo;s reasonable and mine
      may not agree. Look here, now, what d&rsquo;ye say to two hundred pounds?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Two hundred pounds!&rsquo; cried Conseltine, with well-acted amazement. &lsquo;Oh,
      come, come, Blake!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Come, come!&rsquo; echoed Blake. &lsquo;&rsquo;Tis you that has to come&mdash;I&rsquo;ve
      gone far enough along the road to hell; I&rsquo;ll go no farther unless I&rsquo;m paid
      for it. I want two hundred pounds to-morrow, and I&rsquo;ll have it, or know the
      reason why!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I can&rsquo;t do it, Blake,&rsquo; cried Conseltine.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Very well, then,&rsquo; said Blake, &lsquo;his lordship can, and I&rsquo;ll not only get
      two hundred, but ease my aching conscience at the same time.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I think you&rsquo;re hard,&rsquo; said Conseltine. &lsquo;Come, Blake; our interests stand
      or fall together. Look at the affair all round, pro and con. You might get
      that two hundred from Henry, but &rsquo;twould be all you&rsquo;d get. Now,
      serve my interest, and Dick&rsquo;s here, and you&rsquo;re safe for life. Have I ever
      refused you money when you asked for it?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;That&rsquo;s all right,&rsquo; said Blake; &lsquo;don&rsquo;t refuse me now!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well,&rsquo; groaned Conseltine, &lsquo;if you must have it you must.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Bedad I must,&rsquo; returned the other, with a nod full of meaning. &lsquo;Is it a
      bargain?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, it&rsquo;s a bargain.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;To-morrow, mind.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, to-morrow.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Good! Then I&rsquo;ll drug my conscience and accept the solatium. And now I&rsquo;m
      goin&rsquo; home.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Very well,&rsquo; said Conseltine; &lsquo;I&rsquo;ll see you to-morrow.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;All right!&rsquo; retorted Blake, with a disfavouring eye on Richard. &lsquo;Don&rsquo;t
      bring the cub with you. I can stand the old sinner, but not the young
      one.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      He reeled from the room, and Conseltine&rsquo;s glance, as it followed him, was
      full of a dark and concentrated loathing.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;The insolent scoundrel!&rsquo; said Richard, when he was out of hearing. &lsquo;Why
      do you stand him? What is his hold over you?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I hope you&rsquo;ll never need to know,&rsquo; returned his father, draining his
      glass. &lsquo;Damn him! I wish he was in the grave.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;He&rsquo;s going there as fast as drink can take him,&rsquo; said Richard.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I feel inclined sometimes,&rsquo; said his amiable parent, &lsquo;to give him a lift
      on the journey.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
