    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER X.&mdash;ANOTHER INTERVIEW.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">T</span>he shades of
      evening were beginning to envelop the landscape as Peebles made his slow
      and toilsome way towards Blake&rsquo;s Hall. The old man had been in a ferment
      of excitement all day long, and nothing but his long years of habit as
      chief officer and general director of Lord Kilpatrick&rsquo;s household had
      sufficed to hold him back from fulfilling his momently recurring desire to
      throw his duties to the winds for that day, and at once proceed to put to
      Blake the question dictated to him by Moya Macartney. His discomposure had
      not escaped the notice of his master, who, since the shock occasioned by
      Desmond&rsquo;s renunciation of him and his abrupt departure from the house, had
      kept his room, and had resented all approaches, even that of his favourite
      Dulcie, with an exaggeration of his usual snappish ill-temper.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What the deuce are you dreaming about, Peebles?&rsquo; he had asked, as the old
      servitor made some slight blunder in the service at his master&rsquo;s solitary
      dinner-table.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;If ye had an inkling of what I am dreaming about,&rsquo; Peebles had responded,
      with his customary drawl, &lsquo;ye&rsquo;d be in nae such a hurry to speer, maybe.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      At which his lordship had muttered an angry &lsquo;Pshaw!&rsquo; and turned his face
      away.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Is there any news of&mdash;of Desmond?&rsquo; he asked a minute later.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;No, my lord,&rsquo; answered Peebles; &lsquo;none that I ken o&rsquo;.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      He was in so mortal a dread of prematurely letting slip the secret of
      Moya&rsquo;s presence in the neighbourhood that he would not trust himself to
      approach the subject at all.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Where is he?&rsquo; asked Kilpatrick.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;They say he&rsquo;s at Doolan&rsquo;s farm,&rsquo; answered Peebles.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;They say!&rsquo; snapped his lordship. &lsquo;As if you didn&rsquo;t know where the boy is,
      you disingenuous old brute!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Oh ay!&rsquo; said Peebles tranquilly. &lsquo;Swear at me, wi&rsquo; a&rsquo; my heart, if it
      will ease your lordship&rsquo;s heart, or your conscience.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Kilpatrick pushed his plate aside.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Take these things away and bring the wine.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Peebles obeyed, and filled his master&rsquo;s glass, after which he lingered for
      a moment.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well, Peebles, well? Have you anything to say?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Just that I&rsquo;m going oot for an hour or twa. I hae a visit to make. If ye
      want anything in my absence the flunkey will look after ye.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Very good,&rsquo; answered Kilpatrick, who thought he knew the object of
      Peebles&rsquo; visit. &lsquo;Peebles!&rsquo; he called, as the old man reached the door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;My lord!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Has&mdash;has the boy any resources&mdash;any funds?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Not that I ken o&rsquo;,&rsquo; answered Peebles. &lsquo;He was aye too open-handed.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well, if he wants money&mdash;he wouldn&rsquo;t take it from me, I suppose&mdash;lend
      him what he asks, and look to me for repayment. There, there, that will
      do.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Peebles saluted and retired, and set out half an hour later for Blake&rsquo;s
      Hall. Entering the rude sitting-room, he made out, through the gathering
      shadows, the figure of Blake leaning on the table.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;In his general condition, the drunken wastrel!&rsquo; said Peebles. &rsquo;Tis
      odd but he&rsquo;s sae drunk he&rsquo;ll not understand me when I speak to him. Mr.
      Blake! Mr. Blake!&rsquo; He shook the recumbent figure gently at first, and then
      more roughly, and at last elicited a husky growl. &lsquo;Mr. Blake! Wake up, and
      speak to me. Man, I&rsquo;ve news for ye, and a question to ask o&rsquo; ye. Wake up,
      wake up, for the love o&rsquo; Heaven!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Blake swayed back in his seat and opened his eyes. His first act, half
      unconscious, was to hold out his hand towards the bottle, which Peebles
      snatched from him with the quickness of a conjurer.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ye&rsquo;ve had enough o&rsquo; that for one while, ye disgraceful object,&rsquo; he said.
      &lsquo;Wake up, I tell ye! Wake up, and tell me what I want to know.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Oh, &rsquo;tis you, Misther Peebles!&rsquo; cried Blake.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ay, &rsquo;tis mysel&rsquo;,&rsquo; returned Peebles. &lsquo;I&rsquo;ve news for ye, when ye&rsquo;re
      sufficiently sober to hear it.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Blake, like the practised toper he was, pulled himself together, and
      succeeded in looking solemnly and preternaturally sober.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;We&rsquo;re alone?&rsquo; asked the old Scot, glancing cautiously round.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;We are,&rsquo; said Blake. &lsquo;Biddy&rsquo;s gone to the village for more whisky.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Then listen,&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;Moya Macartney&rsquo;s alive!&rsquo; He made the
      communication slowly and distinctly, and paused to mark its effect.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Bedad! that&rsquo;s true!&rsquo; returned Blake, as calmly as if Peebles had said
      &lsquo;Good-day.&rsquo; &lsquo;Ye ken it!&rsquo; cried the old man. &lsquo;And how the deil d&rsquo;ye ken
      it?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;That&rsquo;s my business, sir,&rsquo; said Blake. &lsquo;I <i>do</i> know it. She was in
      the churchyard last night wid a Scotch gentleman of your acquaintance!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      It was difficult to throw Peebles off his mental balance for long at a
      time, and, surprised as he was at Blake&rsquo;s knowledge of the interview of
      the preceding night, he went on with a perfect apparent calm:
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Weel, it should lighten your heart! Ay! ye should fall on your knees and
      thank God, who&rsquo;s kinder to ye than ye deserve, that ye have not that puir
      lassie&rsquo;s death on your conscience!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Have ye come here to preach?&rsquo; asked Blake.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Na, na!&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;That&rsquo;s not my business, but it&rsquo;s yours, Mr. Ryan
      O&rsquo;Connor, if a&rsquo; tales are true!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      There could be no mistaking the effect of this speech on Blake. He half
      rose from his seat, clutching the sides of the table with trembling hands,
      and stared at Peebles with his eyes standing out of his head with
      surprise.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And how the thunder did you know <i>that?</i>&rsquo; he asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;That&rsquo;s <i>my</i> business,&rsquo; retorted the old Scotchman dryly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Holy powers!&rsquo; muttered Blake, falling back into his chair, and passing
      his hand across his eyes in a bewildered fashion. &lsquo;&rsquo;Tis dreamin&rsquo; I
      am!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Listen to me, Patrick Blake,&rsquo; said Peebles solemnly. &lsquo;I met Moya
      Macartney last night. Poor lass! Her spirit&rsquo;s sadly broken. Says she to me&mdash;&ldquo;Peebles,
      it&rsquo;s eighteen years since I spread the report of my own death; my hair is
      white, and my heart is broken; gang to Mr. Blake and ask him, as he values
      his own soul, to tell ye if ever he was in holy orders.&rdquo;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Blake breathed hard, staring at Peebles with a face gone white.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Answer!&rsquo; cried the old man, &lsquo;and for God&rsquo;s sake answer truly!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well, then,&rsquo; said Blake, &lsquo;I was; but not when I married Moya Macartney to
      Lord Kilpatrick.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Had they unfrocked ye?&rsquo; asked Peebles. &lsquo;Tell me that!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;d unfrocked myself,&rsquo; answered Blake. &lsquo;The Bishop said I was a disgrace
      and scandal to the Church, and took from me the only cure of souls I ever
      had.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;But at the time ye married Moya were ye drummed out o&rsquo; the Kirk?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Devil the drum about it,&rsquo; responded Blake. &lsquo;The Bishop persuaded me to
      quit, so I just civilly retired. &rsquo;Twas convanient at the time, for
      sure I had creditors enough to man a Queen&rsquo;s ship.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;But ye had been a priest, and properly ordained?&rsquo; asked Peebles.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Faith, I was as well ordained as any priest need be. What the divil&rsquo;s the
      matter wid ye?&rsquo; he asked, as Peebles sprang from the seat he had taken and
      broke into a Highland fling. &lsquo;Is it mad ye are?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Clean daft wi&rsquo; joy!&rsquo; cried the old man. &lsquo;Gie&rsquo;s your hand, man!&rsquo; He seized
      Blake&rsquo;s hand and wrung it heartily. &lsquo;By the piper that played before
      Moses, ye&rsquo;re the Reverend Mr. Blake still!&mdash;and by that same token
      Moya Macartney is Lady Kilpatrick, and Desmond Macartney is Desmond
      Consel-tine, his lordship&rsquo;s son and heir!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The mention of the name of Conseltine electrified Blake. He clutched his
      whisky-muddled head in both hands, staring wildly before him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;My God!&rsquo; he cried suddenly, &lsquo;is it dreamin&rsquo; that I am? No, by the Lord,
      &rsquo;tis no dream, sir! Get up, man, get up! &rsquo;Tis no time to be
      sittin&rsquo; here! They mean mischief&mdash;already it may be too late!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Too late! Too late for what?&rsquo; cried the old man.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Richard Conseltine and his boy, and Feagus the attorney&mdash;bad cess to
      the lot of &rsquo;em&mdash;were here this forenoon. They know Moya&rsquo;s
      alive! They know where she lives! Oh, my head, my head! what was it the
      blackguards said? Ah!&rsquo; he screamed, &lsquo;the mill! &rsquo;tis at Larry&rsquo;s mill
      that Moya&rsquo;s living!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes!&rsquo; cried Peebles. &lsquo;She&rsquo;s there. But what of that? Speak, man! what is
      it?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;They mean to burn the mill, and her with it!&rsquo; cried Blake. &lsquo;For the love
      o&rsquo; God, run and find Desmond, and get Moya out o&rsquo; the place. &rsquo;Twas
      here that they plotted it. Man alive, I believe they mean murder!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Murder!&rsquo; gasped Peebles.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Isn&rsquo;t it life or death to them to keep Moya out o&rsquo; the way? Run, man! Run
      every step o&rsquo; the road! Ye&rsquo;ve time to save her yet. They daren&rsquo;t try it
      before nightfall. Doolan&rsquo;s farm is on the way, and ye&rsquo;ll find Desmond
      there. If ever ye loved him, run!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Peebles, knowing the men with whom he had to deal, needed no further
      warning, but after a few more hasty words with Blake, ran rather than
      walked from Blake&rsquo;s Hall.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0011" id="link2HCH0011"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XI.&mdash;MOTHER AND SON.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">P</span>eebles, though
      weary with his unwonted vigil in the early morning and the anxiety of the
      day, made good speed to Doolan&rsquo;s farm, urged as he was by those most
      powerful of stimulants, love and fear. It was a long and rough road, but a
      younger and stronger man than the old Scot might have been satisfied with
      the speed at which he covered it. He arrived panting at the humble cabin,
      where the farmer and his family, with Desmond among them, were just
      sitting down to the plain but plentiful evening meal of potatoes and
      buttermilk, supplemented by a rasher of bacon in honour of the guest, whom
      Doolan felt a great pride in entertaining, and who would have found a
      welcome equally warm at almost any house in the district.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;By my soul!&rsquo; said the hospitable farmer, as Peebles broke into the room
      and fell exhausted into the nearest chair; &lsquo;&rsquo;tis me lord&rsquo;s butler&mdash;&rsquo;tis
      Mr. Peebles! The top o&rsquo; the evening to ye, sor. Bridget, I&rsquo;m thinkin&rsquo; Mr.
      Peebles will be takin&rsquo; a dhrop o&rsquo; whisky. Saints above! what&rsquo;s wrong wi&rsquo;
      ye, sor?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Peebles slowly panted his breath back, while the farmer and his wife&mdash;the
      latter a ruddy, handsome peasant woman, who had been Desmond&rsquo;s nurse
      eighteen years before&mdash;stood solicitously over him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Get the bottle, Bridget,&rsquo; said the farmer. &lsquo;The poor gentleman&rsquo;s clane
      blown.
    </p>
    <p>
      Peebles took a mouthful of the liquor, and felt the better for it.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What is it at all?&rsquo; asked Desmond.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Faith, ye look as if you&rsquo;d seen a ghost. What is it, old friend?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You must come with me, Desmond,&rsquo; said the old man. &lsquo;I&rsquo;ve news for ye&mdash;news
      that will keep no longer.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;If &rsquo;tis good news,&rsquo; said Desmond, &lsquo;sure &rsquo;tis welcome, and
      all the more welcome for being unexpected.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Good!&rsquo; cried Peebles&mdash;&lsquo;it&rsquo;s the best! It&rsquo;s better than I ever dared
      to hope!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Faith, then,&rsquo; returned the boy, &lsquo;let&rsquo;s have it!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Not here, laddie, not here!&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;&rsquo;Tis only in your
      private ear that I can whisper it yet.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;We&rsquo;ll lave ye alone,&rsquo; said the honest farmer. &lsquo;Come, Bridget; come,
      children.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;No, no!&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;I&rsquo;ve no time to bide. Ye must come wi&rsquo; me,
      Desmond. It&rsquo;s not a&rsquo; good news I bring ye. There&rsquo;s danger near one ye
      love, laddie.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Dulcie?&rsquo; cried Desmond.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;No&mdash;Lady Dulcie&rsquo;s safe, for a&rsquo; I ken, and I saw her not three hours
      syne, the bonnie doo, blooming like the rose o&rsquo; Sharon. Come, lad, put on
      your hat&mdash;I&rsquo;m rested noo. We&rsquo;ll gang together, and I&rsquo;ll tell ye as we
      gang.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Desmond obeyed, in a great state of bewilderment, and Peebles, when they
      were some hundred yards away from the farm, began his story by a question:
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ye&rsquo;ll remember the poor woman ye met last night in the kirkyard?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes,&rsquo; answered Desmond.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Man,&rsquo; said Peebles, &lsquo;I scarce know how to tell ye, or if ye&rsquo;ll believe me
      when I&rsquo;ve tellt ye. Maybe ye&rsquo;ll think I&rsquo;m daft or dreaming. You&rsquo;ve just
      got to prepare yourself for the greatest shock ye ever had in your life.
      It well-nigh dinged the soul oot o&rsquo; me wi&rsquo; surprise when I heard it, and
      it will hit ye sairer still, I&rsquo;m thinking.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The old man&rsquo;s voice was so tremulous with emotion that Desmond stopped
      short, and peered into his face questioningly in the pale moonlight which
      was struggling with the thick dust of the summer night.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;For God&rsquo;s sake, Peebles,&rsquo; he said, &lsquo;what is it?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It&rsquo;s just this,&rsquo; returned the Scot. &lsquo;That poor woman was Moya Macartney&mdash;your
      own mother!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      For some seconds Peebles&rsquo; speech carried no emotion to Desmond&rsquo;s mind.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;My mother!&rsquo; he repeated, in a voice whose only expression was one of pure
      bewilderment. &lsquo;My mother?&mdash;Moya Macartney?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ay,&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;She that was dead is alive. &rsquo;Tis a long story,
      and I&rsquo;ve neither time nor breath to tell you all. She spread the report of
      her own death eighteen years ago, and went across the seas to America. All
      these long, weary years, she&rsquo;s denied her heart the only pleasure it could
      ever know&mdash;the pleasure of seeing her son&rsquo;s face and hearing his
      voice. At last she could bear it no longer&mdash;she came. It was she you
      talked wi&rsquo; last night in the kirkyard, she who kissed your forehead and
      gied you her blessing.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Desmond clutched at his throat with a choking sob.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;For God&rsquo;s sake, laddie,&rsquo; cried the old man, &lsquo;don&rsquo;t break down noo!
      There&rsquo;s work to be done. You don&rsquo;t know all yet, nor the half o&rsquo;t.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;My mother!&rsquo; cried Desmond. &lsquo;My mother!&rsquo; He took off his soft felt hat,
      crushing it in his hand, and pulled his collar open, stifling with
      surprise and emotion. Peebles, seeing it vain to continue his story for
      the moment, paused, waiting till the first shock of his communication
      should have passed away. &lsquo;My mother!&rsquo; Desmond repeated again, after an
      interval. He spoke mechanically, with an utter lack of emotion in voice
      and manner. &lsquo;My mother! Well?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;The laddie&rsquo;s stunned wi&rsquo; the intelligence,&rsquo; said Peebles to himself, &lsquo;and
      small wonder. Can you understand what I&rsquo;m saying, Desmond?&rsquo; he asked,
      taking the lad&rsquo;s arm. &lsquo;We must gang on, lad. There&rsquo;ll maybe be serious
      work for us this night. D&rsquo;ye understand me?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes,&rsquo; said Desmond slowly, his mind still feeling numbed and dim. &lsquo;I can
      hear what you say, Mr. Peebles, but it&mdash;it all seems so strange. Is
      it dreaming that I am?&rsquo; &lsquo;&rsquo;tis no dream,&rsquo; answered Peebles. &lsquo;It&rsquo;s as
      real as the soil beneath your feet, and as true as God&rsquo;s above ye. Pull
      yerself together, lad, pull yerself together!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well,&rsquo; said Desmond, resuming his way in obedience to the impetus of
      Peebles&rsquo; hand, &lsquo;go on&mdash;I&rsquo;ll try to understand.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;She came back,&rsquo; continued Peebles&mdash;speaking slowly, that the words
      might better penetrate the stunned intelligence of his companion&mdash;&lsquo;she
      came back a&rsquo; that weary way just to see the face and hear the voice o&rsquo; the
      bairn she&rsquo;d suffered for eighteen years ago. But, laddie, she&rsquo;s had
      strange news! You don&rsquo;t ken all the sorrowfu&rsquo; story. I tauld you, when
      that young cub, your cousin, taunted you wi&rsquo; the accident o&rsquo; your birth,
      never to think shame o&rsquo; your mother. I&rsquo;ve had no chance since to tell you
      more; I must tell it noo. Your mother was entrapped by a sham marriage&mdash;or,
      at least, the marriage was believed to be a sham. It was Blake of Blake&rsquo;s
      Hall who officiated as priest. Somehow, Moya surmised that Blake might
      really have been a priest, and asked me to gang till him and speer if it
      was so. I went this afternoon and saw him, and he confessed that he had
      been in holy orders, and that, though the Bishop had ta&rsquo;en his cure o&rsquo;
      souls from him, he had never been legally unfrocked. D&rsquo;ye ken what <i>that</i>
      means, laddie?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;My brain&rsquo;s reeling,&rsquo; said Desmond; &lsquo;I understand nothing.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It means,&rsquo; cried the old man, his voice breaking with glad emotion&mdash;&lsquo;it
      means that you&rsquo;re Desmond Conseltine, my master&rsquo;s legitimate son and heir,
      the next Lord Kilpatrick! Oh, laddie, it&rsquo;s brave news&mdash;it&rsquo;s brave
      news&mdash;and my heart was just bursting to tell it!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Desmond spoke no word, and his silence after the communication of the
      tidings a little frightened his old friend, who peered into his face as
      they walked on quietly side by side.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Hae ye nothing to say, Desmond?&rsquo; he asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What can I say?&rsquo; asked Desmond. &lsquo;Where is my mother?&rsquo; he asked suddenly.
      &lsquo;Is it to her that ye&rsquo;re taking me?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ay,&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;We&rsquo;re gaun to Larry&rsquo;s mill, and there we&rsquo;ll find her.
      Desmond, my man, she mustn&rsquo;t stay there. There&rsquo;s danger abroad.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      They were in the middle of the wide, waste country, but the old man could
      not repress the searching look he cast around him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;She has ill-wishers, blackguards, who&rsquo;ll stick at nothing to gain their
      cruel ends. Blake told me this afternoon of a thing I find it hard to
      credit. Your uncle, Richard Conseltine, and his son, and that scoundrel
      Feagus, <i>know</i> that Moya&rsquo;s alive, and where she&rsquo;s living. Feagus saw
      her wi&rsquo; me in the kirkyard, and listened to our talk. Blake thinks they
      might molest her while she&rsquo;s there asleep! We&rsquo;ll just hope it&rsquo;s nothing
      but one of his drunken havers, but I&rsquo;ve kent Richard Conseltine for
      well-nigh thirty years, and, man, he&rsquo;s a mean creature. There&rsquo;s not much
      he&rsquo;d stick at, I&rsquo;m thinking, for the price is the title and estates of
      Kilpatrick. Anyway, &rsquo;tis just sober prudence to warn Moya and get
      her awa&rsquo; oot o&rsquo; danger. Her proper place is the Castle, but if she&rsquo;ll no
      consent to gang there, we&rsquo;ll just find her another shelter for awhile.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      While Peebles and Desmond were earnestly discussing the strange news of
      her resurrection and reappearance, Moya Macartney was seated alone in the
      desolate tenement known to the country people as &lsquo;Larry&rsquo;s Mill.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      It was a dreary, tumble-down place, ill-fitted for human habitation, and
      the &lsquo;Larry&rsquo; by whom it had been owned had long gone the way of all flesh.
      The house itself was built on wooden pillars, and consisted of an upper
      and a lower chamber; the former utterly abandoned, save in the spring of
      the year, when it was temporarily occupied by an old shepherd; the latter
      now and again used as a sort of byre, or shelter-place for cattle. A rough
      ladder, several rungs or which had fallen away, led from the under to the
      upper room.
    </p>
    <p>
      The mill-wheel itself, choked with filth and weeds, stood still and
      broken, the waters of the stream which had once turned it forcing their
      way through its torn fissures and gaps, and forming a slimy pool. On the
      night of which we write there had been heavy rains, and the stream,
      swollen and black, was pouring through the moveless wheel with the force
      and the roar of a torrent.
    </p>
    <p>
      A truckle-bed with a coarse straw mattress, and a few coarse utensils,
      were the only furniture of the upper room. The floor was strewn with
      straw. A rude window looked down on the wheel and on the dismal pool
      beneath, and as the water roared, and the wind blew, the whole building
      shook as if about to be swept away.
    </p>
    <p>
      The sound of someone stirring below startled the woman as she stood at the
      window gazing silently out into the night.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Who&rsquo;s there?&rsquo; she cried, turning and looking down the open trap-door
      which opened on the ladder.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Sure it&rsquo;s only me, ma&rsquo;am,&rsquo; said a voice&mdash;&lsquo;Larry Monaghan! I&rsquo;ve a
      message to ye from my mother, at the new mill beyant.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      As the man spoke, his head protruded through the trap-door.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I see ye&rsquo;ve a light convanient,&rsquo; he said, pointing to a tallow candle
      which stood above the disused fireplace.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Yes, sure,&rsquo; answered Moya.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Kape it burning, to drive away the rats, but mind the sparks&mdash;the
      ould timber&rsquo;s like touchwood. But sure it&rsquo;s not that I came to say. My
      mother bids ye come over with me to the new mill, and shelter there, for
      sure this is no place for a decent woman.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It&rsquo;s only for one more night,&rsquo; replied Moya, &lsquo;and then I&rsquo;ll be laving for
      my own home in the south. Though I thank your kind mother all the same.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Saints above!&rsquo; murmured Larry. &lsquo;It&rsquo;s not a wink of shleep I could get
      here! They&rsquo;re sayin&rsquo; the place is haunted by the fairies.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Sure they won&rsquo;t harm a poor soul like me!&rsquo; cried Moya, with a musical
      laugh.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Thin ye won&rsquo;t come? It&rsquo;s only a short stretch down the hillside.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;ll stay where I am, thank you,&rsquo; was the reply. &lsquo;I&rsquo;m a sound sleeper,
      and even when I&rsquo;m waking, I&rsquo;ve my thoughts for company. It will be getting
      late?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Past ten o&rsquo;clock,&rsquo; said Larry, &lsquo;and the rain&rsquo;s falling heavily. I&rsquo;m
      concerned to leave ye here, in a place so lonesome!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;The Lord will watch over me!&rsquo; answered Moya, crossing herself.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Amin!&rsquo; said the man. &lsquo;Then I&rsquo;ll say good-night!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Good-night!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      With a dubious shake of the head, Larry disappeared, and immediately
      afterwards she heard the sound of his retreating footsteps below. He was
      whistling as he went, doubtless to keep up his courage, for, like most of
      his class, he was superstitious. Presently all was silent, save for the
      dismal murmur of wind and water. Left alone, Moya sat on the bedside,
      looking at vacancy and thinking. Presently, with a deep sigh, she rose,
      placed the lighted candle for safety in a tin bowl on the floor close to
      the bedside, and then, kneeling down, covered her face with her hands and
      prayed.
    </p>
    <p>
      For a long time she remained thus, praying silently. The wind howled, and
      the water roared, but she did not stir. When at last she rose, her fair
      face looked calm and peaceful, as if the hand of an angel had been placed
      upon her suffering brow. Then she threw herself on the bed, and after a
      time fell asleep.
    </p>
    <p>
      How long she slept she never knew; but she was wearied out, and her sleep
      was sound. Suddenly, with a start of terror, she awakened. The candle had
      gone out, and the place was in total darkness. As she lay trembling and
      listening, she heard, above the moan of the elements, the sound of
      something moving in the room below, and saw, through the trapdoor, a gleam
      like the light from a lanthorn.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Who&rsquo;s there?&rsquo; she cried.
    </p>
    <p>
      There was no answer, but the light immediately disappeared.
    </p>
    <p>
      Moya was not superstitious, and much sorrow had given her unusual courage.
      She sat up in bed, listening, and heard again a sound from below&mdash;this
      time like retreating footsteps.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Sure it was only my fancy,&rsquo; she thought, &lsquo;when I seemed to see a light
      yonder. &rsquo;Twill only be some of the poor mountain cattle sheltering
      from the storm.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      But at that moment a red gleam came from the room below, and before she
      could spring from her bed and look down the gleam had become a flame,
      lighting up the place like dawn. Conscious now of a real and awful peril,
      she endeavoured to descend the ladder, but a column of mingled smoke and
      flame drove her back, suffocating.
    </p>
    <p>
      The room below was a sheet of fire, and piled against the walls was a heap
      of dry hay and straw, burning brightly, with flames that leapt up and
      caught the rotten timber. With a scream she again attempted to descend,
      but was instantly driven back. Then, scarcely knowing what she did, she
      closed the trap-door, and rushing to the window, threw it open.
    </p>
    <p>
      She realized the truth now. The sounds she had heard, the light she had
      seen, had been made by human beings, and whether by design or by accident,
      the mill had been set on fire. Poor soul, she did not yet understand that
      there were men living in the world who would do even a deed like that to
      compass a fellow-creature&rsquo;s death.
    </p>
    <p>
      As she stood terror-stricken, a tongue of fire crept through the floor and
      caught the loose straw with which it was strewn. At this fresh horror she
      uttered a piercing shriek, for escape seemed impossible. As her voice rose
      on the night, it was answered by another from the darkness.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Mother! mother!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Her heart stood still. Was she dreaming? Whose voice could it be that
      uttered that holy name? She leant out over the mill-wheel, and saw beyond
      her in the darkness the glimmer of a lanthorn.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Help! help!&rsquo; she cried; and as she cried the whole place seemed rocking
      beneath, and thick clouds of smoke and tongues of fire came up through the
      heating floor. Then again she heard the voice, crying and imploring.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Mother! mother!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Who&rsquo;s that?&rsquo; she cried.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Desmond&mdash;your son Desmond!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Desmond! Her son! Even in her dire and awful peril she felt a thrill of
      delicious joy.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Save me, Desmond, save me!&rsquo; she cried.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;The water-wheel!&rsquo; answered Desmond. Climb out from the window, stand on
      the wheel, and lape for your life into the pool below!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Moya hesitated, and again, as the flame and smoke thickened behind her,
      uttered a despairing scream.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;&rsquo;Tis your only chance for life,&rsquo; called the voice. &lsquo;Jump, mother
      darling! Sure I&rsquo;ll be near to help ye! Jump, for the love of God!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      It was that or being burned alive. The whole mill was now one sheet of
      flame, and the fire scorched her as she stood, while the wooden floor
      crackled and split beneath her feet. Crossing herself, and consigning her
      soul to God, she scrambled out on the wheel and clung there on hands and
      knees, exposed to the full force of wind and rain.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Jump, mother!&rsquo; cried Desmond once more. She fluttered forward with a cry,
      and slipped rather than fell with a heavy splash into the boiling waters
      of the pool. As she did so her senses left her; she seemed to be sucked
      down, down into some awful abyss; then she was conscious of nothing more.
    </p>
    <p>
      When her eyes opened, she was lying on the bank of the stream, with the
      light from a lanthorn flashing into her face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Mother! mother!&rsquo; cried the voice she had heard before. &lsquo;It&rsquo;s Desmond&mdash;your
      son Desmond!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      His arms were round her neck, her head was on his bosom. Peebles, holding
      the lanthorn, bent over them, tears streaming down his wrinkled face.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Desmond&mdash;my boy!&rsquo; she murmured.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Mother, my mother!&rsquo; he answered, sobbing over her.
    </p>
    <p>
      He had watched her drop into the mill-pool, and then had plunged in to her
      rescue, catching her as she was swept down towards the fall below the
      mill, and swimming with her to the bank whereon she now lay.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
