    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XIII.&mdash;FATHER AND SON.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">D</span>uring breakfast
      next morning at the Castle the two Conseltines, father and son, who were
      usually punctual in their appearance at meal hours, descended late. They
      were pale and quiet; and Richard, who had his nerves very much less under
      control than had his astute and resolute parent, was so obviously ill at
      ease as to bring down upon himself the notice and comments of his
      lordship. The old nobleman, sick of the seclusion of his solitary chamber,
      had appeared at the breakfast table, in hopes that a little cheerful
      society might aid in dissipating the unwelcome reflections which, since
      Desmond&rsquo;s departure from the Castle, had beset his waking hours and broken
      his nightly rest. At no time gifted with the most equable temper in the
      world, he was particularly snappish and irritable that morning.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Your lordship will no&rsquo; hae heard the news, I&rsquo;m thinking,&rsquo; said Peebles,
      standing at the sideboard and breaking in upon the uneasy silence. His
      eyes dwelt, as if by accident, upon Richard Consel-tine&rsquo;s face as he
      spoke, and the young man&rsquo;s pale complexion assumed a greenish hue.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What news are you talking about?&rsquo; asked Kilpatrick.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;There was a fire last night,&rsquo; answered Peebles.
    </p>
    <p>
      Richard, conscious of his father&rsquo;s coldly threatening eye, spilled half
      the contents of the glass of brandy-and-soda by which he had that morning
      replaced the soberer beverages usually in demand at the breakfast table,
      and conveyed the remainder to his lips with a shaking hand.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;A fire! Where?&rsquo; asked Kilpatrick.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;At the old mill up by the burn,&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;&rsquo;Twas burned to
      the ground, I&rsquo;m told, and there&rsquo;s some talk of an old peasant woman, a
      gangrel strange body that they had gien shelter to, having been burned wi&rsquo;
      it.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;God bless my soul!&rsquo; murmured his lordship. &lsquo;Has the body been found?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Richard emitted an involuntary gasp, and clung with his feet to the leg of
      the table.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;No,&rsquo; returned Peebles, &lsquo;not yet. There&rsquo;s just the chance it never may be.
      A good part o&rsquo; the blazing timbers fell into the burn and were carried
      awa&rsquo;, and it&rsquo;s like eneuch the body went wi&rsquo; them&mdash;or maybe they&rsquo;ll
      come upon it digging among the ruins.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Who was the woman?&rsquo; asked Dulcie,
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Does anybody know her?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Nobody that I ken o&rsquo;,&rsquo; returned Peebles, with an immovable face. &lsquo;A bit
      tramp body.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Deuced odd,&rsquo; said Kilpatrick. &lsquo;How could a place like that, miles away
      from anywhere, catch fire? Is there any suspicion of arson?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;&rsquo;Deed,&rsquo; said Peebles, &lsquo;I don&rsquo;t know why there should be. Who is there
      that wad do siccan mischief? To be sure,&rsquo; he added, with a reflective air,
      &lsquo;the woman might have enemies. Those tramps are a waesome lot to deal wi&rsquo;&mdash;but
      it&rsquo;s most likely that she did it hersel&rsquo; by accident, poor thing. We&rsquo;ll
      just hope so, for the sake o&rsquo; human charity&mdash;till we get further
      information, anyway.&rsquo; He looked at Richard again as he spoke the last
      words, and had some difficulty in repressing any sign of the angry scorn
      he felt at sight of the young man&rsquo;s livid face. &lsquo;It&rsquo;s hard on Larry,
      dacent lad,&rsquo; he continued.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;m thinking that your lordship might do worse than start a subscription
      for him.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Certainly, certainly,&rsquo; said Kilpatrick.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;ll give five pounds. You have my leave, Peebles, to say so, and to ask
      for subscriptions in my name.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;ll give five,&rsquo; said Dulcie.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I shall be glad to follow so good an example,&rsquo; said Conseltine. He strove
      hard to speak in his usual smooth fashion, but his voice sounded harsh and
      unsteady to his own ears. He gave Richard an angrily prompting look, and
      the boy tried to speak, but his tongue rattled against the roof of his
      mouth. &lsquo;I thought you would,&rsquo; said Conseltine, quickly interpreting the
      inarticulate sound issuing from his son&rsquo;s throat as an expression of
      charitable sympathy. &lsquo;Put Richard and myself down for ten pounds, if you
      please, Mr. Peebles.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I thank ye, Lady Dulcie and gentlemen,&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;It&rsquo;s good to hae
      feeling hearts, and the means of proving that ye hae them. I&rsquo;ll let ye
      know any later news&mdash;if the body&rsquo;s found, or anything o&rsquo; that kind.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What the devil&rsquo;s the matter with you?&rsquo; his lordship asked of Richard,
      with sudden acerbity. Richard was as white as death, and shivering like a
      leaf.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It&rsquo;s the heat, or&mdash;or something,&rsquo; he managed to stammer out.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Let me help you to your room, my boy,&rsquo; said his father.
    </p>
    <p>
      He rose, and supported Richard from the table, hiding as well as he could
      his pitiable condition.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You cowardly fool!&rsquo; he hissed in his ear, when he had got him to his own
      chamber and locked the door. &lsquo;Do you want to ruin us? What are ye afraid
      of, ye shaking poltroon?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;He knows!&rsquo; gasped Richard; &lsquo;I could see it in his eye; he knows.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Knows!&rsquo; echoed Conseltine scornfully.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What does he know?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;He knows that the woman at the mill was Moya Macartney.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And if he does,&rsquo; said Conseltine, &lsquo;what then? What can he prove?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;He knows more than that, I&rsquo;ll swear!&rsquo; cried Richard. &lsquo;I saw him look at
      me. He knows enough to hang us.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Hang us!&rsquo; repeated the elder. &lsquo;By the saints, I&rsquo;ve a mind to save the
      hangman half his work, you white-livered, croaking coward!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;If <i>he</i> doesn&rsquo;t know, Blake does,&rsquo; said Richard.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Leave Blake to me,&rsquo; said his father.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;ll look after Blake. &rsquo;Twill be a question of money; he&rsquo;ll bleed
      us pretty freely, I expect; but if he opens his mouth too wide I&rsquo;ll bluff
      him, and swear he dreamt it. &rsquo;Tis two against one, any way; two men
      of good position and unblemished record against one drunken vagabond.
    </p>
    <p>
      They can prove nothing, let them talk as they may. Feagus will hold his
      tongue for his own sake, for if the case comes before the court there are
      three to swear that he suggested the business. There&rsquo;s no danger at all,
      except from your cursed cowardice. Pull yourself together, and trust to
      me. They can prove no motive. Why should you and I go burning mills and
      killing old peasant women? Feagus is the only creature alive who knows
      that we were aware of Moya&rsquo;s identity. Keep a cool head, and you&rsquo;ll be
      Lord Kilpatrick before long.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      The task which Peebles had undertaken was no easy one, and the more he
      contemplated it, the more difficult it seemed to grow. He racked his
      brains over the problem of how to make known to one in so precarious a
      condition of health as Lord Kilpatrick the secret of Moya&rsquo;s continued
      existence, and of her presence in the neighbourhood. The difficulty was
      complicated by the cowardly and criminal attempt on her life by two
      members of his lordship&rsquo;s family, for the honour of which the faithful old
      servant was deeply concerned. That two such scoundrels should still be
      permitted to prey on the kindness of his master, and diminish Desmond&rsquo;s
      patrimony, was intolerable; that they should be publicly charged with
      their crime was impossible. Feagus, too, was in the same boat, and must
      also be permitted to escape, for it was impossible to denounce him without
      bringing the crime of the Conseltines to light. But, then, there was the
      chance&mdash;the strong chance&mdash;of the gossip of the countryside
      bringing to their ears the knowledge of Moya&rsquo;s continued existence, and
      what three such scoundrels might do to cover their unsuccessful attempt,
      and to secure their endangered booty, it was hard to say.
    </p>
    <p>
      The need for decisive action was pressing, but in what direction was that
      action to be taken? One course, and one course only, seemed to Peebles
      clear for the moment. It was in his power to secure Moya&rsquo;s safety from any
      further attempt. That could be done by simply telling the two villains now
      in the house that their nefarious proceeding of the night before was
      known. Once resolved, Peebles was as bold a man as any that ever trod
      shoe-leather; and with such a weapon as was furnished by his hold over the
      two Conseltines he would have faced an army. His resolution taken, he
      walked with an assured foot upstairs to Richard&rsquo;s bedroom, and knocked at
      the door; it was opened by the elder man.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I&rsquo;d like a word with you, if you please, Mr. Conseltine,&rsquo; he said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Presently, Mr. Peebles, presently,&rsquo; said the other, who did not care to
      expose his son and confederate to the old man&rsquo;s keen eye in his present
      pitiful condition of nervous excitement. &lsquo;We have business of importance
      together.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It must be business o&rsquo; very great importance,&rsquo; said Peebles, &lsquo;if it can&rsquo;t
      wait till mine is finished.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Conseltine&rsquo;s hard eye dwelt on the old man&rsquo;s face, and his lips twitched
      in a hopeless attempt to maintain their impassivity.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You are importunate, my old friend,&rsquo; he said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ye&rsquo;d better listen to me,&rsquo; returned the grim old servitor.
    </p>
    <p>
      Conseltine stood aside to allow him to enter, and closed and locked the
      door behind him. Richard was seated on the bed. He made a terrible and
      clumsy effort to seem at ease as Peebles&rsquo; gaze passed lightly over him
      before it settled again on his father.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well, sir?&rsquo; said Conseltine as calmly as he could.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Before making the communication I hae to make,&rsquo; said Peebles, his usual
      slow and deliberate drawl more slow and deliberate than ever, &lsquo;I hae to
      tell ye that, but for the honour o&rsquo; the house I&rsquo;ve served man and boy for
      five-and-forty years, I should have conseedered it my duty as a good
      citizen to hand you and your son, Mr. Richard Conseltine, here present,
      into the hands o&rsquo; justice.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Neither of the persons he addressed making any reply to this preamble,
      Peebles continued:
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;When Larry&rsquo;s mill was burned down last night, the woman once known as
      Moya Macartney, best known to you and me, Mr. Conseltine, as Lady
      Kilpatrick, was leeving there.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      That Conseltine knew of Moya&rsquo;s claim to the title Peebles gave her was
      only a shrewd guess of the latter&rsquo;s, but the start and pallor with which
      Conseltine heard the words showed the old man that the shaft had struck
      home.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;The mill,&rsquo; continued Peebles, &lsquo;was fired by you and your son there, in
      complicity wi&rsquo; one Feagus, the lawyer, wi&rsquo; the object of destroying the
      unfortunate lady, your brother&rsquo;s wife.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Richard gave a sort of feeble gulp at this, and cowered terror-stricken on
      the bed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It&rsquo;s by no virtue o&rsquo; yours, Mr. Conseltine, that your wicked will was not
      worked. Moya Macartney, Lady Kilpatrick, is alive and safe. She was
      rescued from death by her son, Desmond Conseltine, sole lawfully begotten
      son and heir of my master, Lord Kilpatrick.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Damn you!&rsquo; cried Richard, leaping from the bed at these words with a
      flash of hysteric anger conquering his fears.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You come and tell us this! Father&mdash;&mdash;!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Hold your tongue!&rsquo; said the elder man quietly. &lsquo;Don&rsquo;t play the fool,
      Richard Conseltine.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Peebles looked at him with a kind of loathing admiration of his courage
      and coolness.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;If you&rsquo;ve any more to say, Mr. Peebles,&rsquo; Conseltine continued, &lsquo;you&rsquo;d
      better get it over.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Just this,&rsquo; said the old man: &lsquo;ye&rsquo;ll hold your tongue about the business
      till I see fit to speak. Ye&rsquo;ll cease to trade on his lordship&rsquo;s
      generosity, and rob the poor lad ye&rsquo;ve kept out of his rights all these
      years, and the poor woman ye&rsquo;ve tried to murder. And if in a day or two ye
      can manage to find some business o&rsquo; sufficient importance to tak&rsquo; ye awa&rsquo;
      oot o&rsquo; this place, and to keep ye awa&rsquo; oot o&rsquo;t for the rest o&rsquo; your
      natural lives, so much the better. I don&rsquo;t think,&rsquo; he added reflectively,
      as he scraped his lean jaws thoughtfully with his long fingers&mdash;&lsquo;I
      don&rsquo;t think there&rsquo;s any ither thing to be arranged. Ye&rsquo;d better keep clear
      o&rsquo; Blake, perhaps.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;One word, Mr. Peebles,&rsquo; said Conseltine, as the old man turned to go.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;When do you intend to break to my brother the news of&mdash;of that woman
      being alive?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I canna preceesely tell ye,&rsquo; returned Peebles. &lsquo;As soon&rsquo;s I think he&rsquo;s
      strong enough to hear it. In the mean time, Mr. Conseltine, ye&rsquo;d best ca&rsquo;
      cannie. I&rsquo;m secret in the game till ye try another move; but if ye do,
      I&rsquo;ll split on ye, as sure as God&rsquo;s in heaven!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0014" id="link2HCH0014"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XIV.&mdash;LADY KILPATRICK.
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">P</span>eebles had left
      the Conseltines barely half an hour when a message was brought to him in
      his pantry that Mr. Blake of Blake&rsquo;s Hall would be glad to have the
      pleasure of a word with him. Blake, being ushered into the old man&rsquo;s
      private room, immediately demanded whisky, and, having been supplied,
      inquired of Peebles what was the news concerning Moya.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I met Larry as I was coming here. Sure, he&rsquo;s like a madman, raving about
      the poor woman that must have been burned wid the mill, though sorra a
      chip of her bones or a rag of her dress have they found.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;They&rsquo;re no likely to find anything,&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;I went straight to
      Desmond last night, and he was just in time to rescue her from the awfu&rsquo;
      death the villains had plotted for her.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Glad am I to know it,&rsquo; said Blake. &lsquo;Are the rogues laid by the heels
      yet?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;No,&rsquo; said Peebles, &lsquo;nor will they be, wi&rsquo; my good will. Man, &rsquo;twould
      break my lord&rsquo;s heart! His ain brother, Mr. Blake! his ain brother&rsquo;s son!
      No, no. They must be let gang, for the honour o&rsquo; the family, though it&rsquo;s a
      hard lump to swallow, and goes terribly against my conscience, that twa
      such wretches should be free while many a decent man&rsquo;s in prison. But
      there&rsquo;s just no help for it. And noo, just tell me, Mr. Blake, are ye
      sober&mdash;sober enough, I mean, to know the value of what ye&rsquo;re saying?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Sober, is it?&rsquo; cried Blake. &lsquo;Soberer than I&rsquo;ve been this five-and-twenty
      years, bad luck to me!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Then listen to me,&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;&rsquo;Twas you that married his
      lordship to Moya Macartney?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;&rsquo;Twas so,&rsquo; returned Blake.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And ye had really been ordained a clerk in holy orders before that time?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I had, but when I performed the ceremony I used a false name.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;That makes no difference,&rsquo; returned Peebles. &lsquo;You were a clergyman, you
      are a clergyman, and a clergyman you&rsquo;ll die. Holy orders are indelible! I
      ken that much, though I&rsquo;m no churchman mysel&rsquo;. Noo, Moya&rsquo;s safe, and it&rsquo;s
      my intention, jest as soon as it can be done withoot chance of damage to
      my lord&rsquo;s health, to break the news to him, and I&rsquo;ll look to you to put
      all possible assistance in the way o&rsquo; proving your possession o&rsquo; the
      necessary power to perform a legal marriage.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;H&rsquo;m!&rsquo; said Blake doubtfully.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And what the deil d&rsquo;ye mean by &ldquo;h&rsquo;m&rdquo;?&rsquo; asked Peebles.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;You&rsquo;re talkin&rsquo; mighty aisy,&rsquo; said Blake, &lsquo;of my givin&rsquo; up the only means
      o&rsquo; livelihood I&rsquo;ve had these years past.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Means o&rsquo; livelihood,&rsquo; repeated Peebles. &lsquo;You&rsquo;re doited, man alive! What
      has this question to do wi&rsquo; your means of livelihood?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Just the blackmail that Dick Conseltine has paid me to hold my tongue,&rsquo;
      replied Blake with a beautiful candour.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;That&rsquo;s all o&rsquo;er now,&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;He kens that Moya&rsquo;s alive, and he
      kens that <i>I</i> ken it. Eh, Patrick Blake,&rsquo; he continued, shaking his
      head reproachfully at the burly figure opposite him, &lsquo;ye&rsquo;ve been a sad
      scoun&rsquo;rel in your time, I doubt. But ye helped to save that puir lass&rsquo;s
      life, and I&rsquo;ll no be hard on ye. What can be done for ye in reason shall
      be done. Maybe the wages o&rsquo; honesty won&rsquo;t amount to as much as the wages
      o&rsquo; sin, but ye&rsquo;ll hae a clearer conscience to mak&rsquo; up the balance. I can
      promise naething, but I&rsquo;ll speak to Desmond and my lord. I&rsquo;m thinking ye&rsquo;d
      be best oot o&rsquo; the country. Some hundred pounds and a passage to America
      would suit ye fine.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Emigration!&rsquo; said Blake. &lsquo;&rsquo;Twas that Dick Conseltine was advising
      the other day. Faix, ye&rsquo;re all in a mighty hurry to get rid o&rsquo; poor old
      Pat Blake. Well, Peebles, I&rsquo;ll trust ye. I&rsquo;ve always found ye square and
      honest, and I like the boy. I&rsquo;d rather see him with the title than that
      ape cub o&rsquo; Dick Conseltine&rsquo;s, any day of the year. As for the help I can
      give ye, well, there&rsquo;s me licence to preach, marry, and bury, signed by
      the Bishop, and granted at Maynooth College. I&rsquo;ve got it at home at
      Blake&rsquo;s Hall to this day, and faith, if that&rsquo;s not enough, I can find a
      score o&rsquo; people at my old cure who&rsquo;ll remember me and swear to my
      identity.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      At this moment he was interrupted by a rap at the pantry door, and a
      servant announced that Peebles was needed in my lord&rsquo;s chamber.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Wait here,&rsquo; said the old man to Blake. &lsquo;I&rsquo;ll no&rsquo; be long.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Peebles mounted the stairs, and found Kilpatrick seated at the open window
      of his room. He gave some commonplace instructions which could quite
      easily have been fulfilled by any other servant in the house. Peebles, who
      knew his master&rsquo;s mind as though he had made him, obeyed the orders, and
      stood at his elbow silently.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Well, Peebles? well?&rsquo; asked Kilpatrick. &lsquo;Well, my lord?&rsquo; said Peebles,
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What are you waiting for?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;For your lordship&rsquo;s orders.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Kilpatrick sat twisting his fingers in a nervous silence for a second or
      two, and then abruptly asked:
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Where&rsquo;s Desmond? I suppose you&rsquo;ve seen him lately?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ay!&rsquo; said Peebles, &lsquo;I saw him last night.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;And what had the young scamp to say for himself? Still on the high horse,
      I suppose? When does he propose to honour my house with his presence
      again?&rsquo; &lsquo;God forgive us!&rsquo; said Peebles, shaking his head at his master
      with a mournful reproof. &lsquo;&ldquo;Still on his high horse,&rdquo; quotha! &rsquo;Tis
      you that are walking wi&rsquo; the bare feet o&rsquo; conscience in the mire o&rsquo;
      repentance, if your silly pride would let ye own till it.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Kilpatrick tried to look angrily at the old man, but the continued slow
      shake of Peebles&rsquo; head, and the calm penetration of the eyes that dwelt on
      his, cowed him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I ask you, Peebles,&rsquo; he cried suddenly, &lsquo;is not my position a hard one?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Sair hard,&rsquo; said Peebles; &lsquo;but ye made it yoursel&rsquo;, and ye hae nae right
      to grumble.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;It&rsquo;s harder than I deserve,&rsquo; cried Kilpatrick. &lsquo;If&mdash;if it was the&mdash;the
      just measure of punishment for&mdash;for that silly indiscretion of years
      ago, I should not complain, but&mdash;&mdash;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;My lord!&rsquo; said Peebles, &lsquo;dinna gang beyond God&rsquo;s patience. &ldquo;Just measure
      o&rsquo; punishment!&rdquo; &ldquo;too hard!&rdquo; I wonder ye hae the presumption to sit in that
      chair, and talk to me that ken the circumstances.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Hold your tongue, confound you!&rsquo; said his master.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;That will I no&rsquo;,&rsquo; returned Peebles, &rsquo;till as your speeritual
      weelwisher and your carnal servant I hae done my best to purge your heart
      o&rsquo; the black vanity ye cherish.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Go to the devil, you canting old scoundrel!&rsquo; screamed Kilpatrick.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;After your lordship,&rsquo; said Peebles suavely, and flowed on before the
      angry old gentleman could stop him. &lsquo;You say your lot&rsquo;s a hard one? You
      complain that Providence is punishing you too severely? Man, ye are just
      like a spoiled child, that sets a house afire in his wantonness, and then
      thinks he&rsquo;s badly treated because he gets his fingers burnt. Your lot a
      hard one! What about the lot o&rsquo; the innocent lass that trusted ye, and
      that ye ruined and slew? What about the bright bonny lad that God put it
      into his mither&rsquo;s heart to send here t&rsquo; ye, that should hae been a sound
      o&rsquo; peace in your ears, a light unto your eyes, a sermon to your
      understanding, ilka day this eighteen years bygone? What about his shame
      and anguish, his loss of respect and belief in all his kind, because you,
      the one man he loved and trusted most, turned to base metal in his sight?
      And ye are hardly treated! Gin ye had your deserts, Henry Conseltine, Lord
      Kilpatrick, ye&rsquo;d be on the treadmill at this minute. There&rsquo;s many an
      honester man than you that&rsquo;s praying God this minute for bread and water
      to stay his carnal pangs, while ye sit here, full o&rsquo; meat, and puffed out
      wi&rsquo; idleness. Ill treated! Ma certie!&rsquo; cried the old man, with a fall from
      an almost Biblical solemnity of phrase to latter-day colloquialism which
      would have seemed ludicrous to any third person. &lsquo;Ye&rsquo;re no blate! Perhaps
      ye&rsquo;d like a step up in the peerage for havin&rsquo; ruined an honest lassie and
      broken a poor lad&rsquo;s heart?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Upon my soul,&rsquo; said Kilpatrick, twisting in his chair, &lsquo;I don&rsquo;t know why
      I stand your infernal impudence.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;For the same reason,&rsquo; returned Peebles, &lsquo;that you stand the infernal
      impudence o&rsquo; your ain conscience. Ye&rsquo;ve been trying to drug and bully <i>that</i>
      into quiet a&rsquo; these years, and ye&rsquo;ve no succeeded yet, and ne&rsquo;er will, the
      Lord be praised! Ye ask,&rsquo; he continued, &lsquo;if Desmond&rsquo;s on his high horse
      yet? Ay, is he&mdash;on a higher horse than ever.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What do you mean?&rsquo; asked Kilpatrick.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Circumstances have come to light this last day or twa,&rsquo; said Peebles,
      &lsquo;that put a new complexion on a&rsquo; this business.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;What circumstances?&rsquo; asked his lordship wonderingly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Strange circumstances,&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;I&rsquo;ve news for ye that&rsquo;ll mak&rsquo; your
      ears to tingle, I&rsquo;m thinking.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Curse you!&rsquo; cried the old man; &lsquo;can&rsquo;t you speak out, instead of jibbering
      and jabbering in this fashion, you old death&rsquo;s-head!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Ye&rsquo;re a foul-mouthed person, Lord Kilpatrick,&rsquo; said Peebles dryly, &lsquo;but
      let that flea stick to the wall. I&rsquo;ve news for ye that it will tak&rsquo;
      courage to listen to.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Man alive!&rsquo; cried Kilpatrick; &lsquo;for the love of God don&rsquo;t waste your time
      and my patience in this fashion! What is your news?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Just this,&rsquo; said the old man slowly and deliberately: &lsquo;The marriage with
      Moya Macartney, that ye believed to be a sham marriage&mdash;the more
      shame to ye for it&mdash;was no&rsquo; a sham at all, but as good a marriage as
      was ever made between man and maid on this earth, and as binding!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Kilpatrick stared at him like one distraught, breathing heavily, and
      grasping the side-pieces of his armchair with twitching fingers.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;&rsquo;Tis sooth I&rsquo;m tellin&rsquo; ye,&rsquo; returned Peebles. &lsquo;Blake was in holy
      orders. He&rsquo;d been deprived of his cure and he performed the ceremony under
      a false name, but he&rsquo;d ne&rsquo;er been disfrocked. Desmond is your lawfully
      begotten son&mdash;your heir!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Kilpatrick&rsquo;s reception of this astounding news fairly astonished the old
      man. After the first dumfoundering effect of the communication had passed,
      Kilpatrick sprang from his chair, his face flushed, his eyes glittering.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Is it true? Is it true?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;True as death!&rsquo; responded Peebles.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Where is he?&rsquo; cried the old man. &lsquo;For God&rsquo;s sake, Peebles, bring him
      here! Let me see him!&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      His face darkened with a sudden expression of doubt.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Peebles,&rsquo; he cried brokenly; &lsquo;you&rsquo;re not playing with me? You&rsquo;re not
      deceiving me? I&rsquo;ve been a good master to you these years past; you
      couldn&rsquo;t&mdash;you wouldn&rsquo;t&mdash;&mdash;&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;God forbid!&rsquo; said Peebles. &lsquo;It&rsquo;s gospel truth.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;But,&rsquo; asked Kilpatrick, &lsquo;why has Blake been silent all these years?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Because,&rsquo; said Peebles, &lsquo;Richard Conseltine has made it worth his while.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;By Heaven!&rsquo; cried the old lord, &lsquo;I&rsquo;ll break every bone in Dick&rsquo;s body!
      Peebles, you don&rsquo;t know what I&rsquo;ve suffered all these years. Even from you
      I&rsquo;ve hidden my miseries. I&rsquo;ve looked at Desmond, standing side by side
      with that ugly cub of Dick&rsquo;s, and ground my teeth to think that I couldn&rsquo;t
      leave the title to him. God bless you, Peebles&mdash;God bless you for the
      news! &lsquo;Fore Gad! I shall go mad with joy. Peebles, I&rsquo;ll double your wages
      if you&rsquo;ll get the boy here in an hour from now. What are you standing
      glowering there for? Run, you old rascal, run, and bring Desmond to me! My
      eyes are hungry for him! I&rsquo;ll acknowledge him before the world! He shall
      marry Dulcie before the week&rsquo;s out, and I&rsquo;ll live to nurse my grandson
      yet! Dick&rsquo;s face will be a sight to see when he learns that I know this.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Peebles did not move. He was revolving in his mind the wisdom of at once
      breaking to Kilpatrick the news that the wife he deemed dead was living.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Desmond shall do that,&rsquo; he said to himself. &lsquo;Ay, Desmond shall do that.
      &rsquo;Twill come better from him. My lord&rsquo;s heart will be softened. &rsquo;Twill
      be less of a shock than if <i>I</i> told him. Ay, ay,&rsquo; he said aloud, as
      Kilpatrick impatiently bade him begone and fetch Desmond. &lsquo;He shall be
      here inside an hour, my lord.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;God bless you, old friend,&rsquo; said his lordship, shaking hands with him.
      &lsquo;You&rsquo;re a pragmatical old Puritan, but you&rsquo;ve taken ten years off my age
      to-day.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      Peebles descended to the pantry, where he found Blake still in intimate
      converse with the whisky bottle.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;Mr. Blake, would ye do my lord and me a service?&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;By my troth, I will, then,&rsquo; said Blake.
    </p>
    <p>
      Peebles called a groom, and bade him prepare a horse and carriage.
    </p>
    <p>
      &lsquo;I want ye, Mr. Blake, to drive to Maguire&rsquo;s cottage over at Cornboy.
      There you&rsquo;ll find Moya Macartney&mdash;tell her she must come with you.
      Then drive on to Doolan&rsquo;s Farm, and pick up Desmond. Bring them both here,
      and I&rsquo;ll have a boy posted in the road to warn me that ye&rsquo;re coming.&rsquo;
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0015" id="link2HCH0015"> </a>
    </p>
